{"title_page": "Debra Sparrow", "text_new": "'''Debra Sparrow''', or \u03b8\u0259li\u03c7\u02b7\u0259l\u02b7\u0259t (Thelliawhatlwit), is a Musqueam weaver, artist and knowledge keeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aboriginal.ubc.ca/2014/07/03/new-ubc-president-welcomed-and-honored-by-first-nations/|title=Musqueam welcomes President Gupta on his first day {{!}} Aboriginal Portal|last=Ward|first=Kevin|website=aboriginal.ubc.ca|access-date=2016-04-18}}</ref> She is self-taught in Salish design, weaving, and jewellery making.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vancitybuzz.com/2015/05/peau-de-loup-scarf-fifa-womens-world-cup/|title=Vancouver Brand Peau De Loup Designs Scarf for 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|last=Kwon|first=Crystal|date=18 May 2015|work=Vancity Buzz|access-date=18 February 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nSparrow was born and raised on the [[Musqueam Indian Band|Musqueam Indian]] Reserve, part of the traditional territories of the Musqueam people, in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. Sparrow credits her grandfather, Ed Sparrow, who lived to be 100 years old and remembered the forcible removal of the Musqueam people from [[Stanley Park]], with giving her \"300 years of stories\" that grounded her in her heritage and enabled her to hear the voices of her ancestors. \"We never stopped dancing, we never stopped singing, we never stopped practising our cultural ways,\" says Sparrow, who considers herself a person who lives and practises traditional ways.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gallerieswest.ca/blogs-and-buzz/%22coast-salish-revival%22%3A-timeless%2C-elegant-art-thrives-thanks/|title=\"Coast Salish Revival\": Timeless, elegant art thrives thanks to visionaries like Simon Charlie|last=Fournier|first=Suzanne|date=23 May 2015|website=Galleries West|publisher=|access-date=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nSparrow is the mother of three grown children.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/but-wheres-the-loonie/article428248|title=But Where's the Loonie?|last=Sekeres|first=Matthew|date=18 August 2009|website=The Globe and Mail|publisher=|access-date=18 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Musqueam weavers ==\nBy the time of Sparrow's childhood the techniques of [[Salish weaving]] were lost to the Musqueam nation. There were no living weavers to teach a new generation; the last known weaver before the revival was Sparrow's great grandmother.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://199.243.64.45/musqueam-sisters-revive-traditional-salish-weaving |title=Musqueam Sisters Revive Traditional Salish Weaving |last= |first= |date=20 November 2009 |website=Four Host Nations |publisher= |access-date=23 February 2016 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1985, Wendy John, Sparrow's eldest sister attended a Salish weaving course at the Vancouver Indian Centre (now the [http://www.vafcs.org/ Vancouver Aboriginal Friendship Centre]). The next year, Sparrow and her younger sister Robyn Sparrow began to study weaving as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=891e7a18-78ee-499b-aab9-0f65938c1e78 |title=Aboriginal Heroes: Spinning a Cloth through Time |last=Griffith |first=Kevin |date=20 June 2008 |website=Canada.com |publisher=CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. |access-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611062844/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=891e7a18-78ee-499b-aab9-0f65938c1e78 |archivedate=11 June 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAlong with her sister Robyn, Sparrow co-founded a group of women weavers in the 1980s who rejuvenated the Salish Weaving tradition.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Musqueam Weavers Source Book|last=Baird|first=Jill Rachel|last2=Johnson|first2=Elizabeth Lominska|publisher=Museum of Anthropology at University of British Columbia|year=2002|isbn=|location=Vancouver, BC|pages=}}</ref> They were able to reconstruct the lost weaving techniques utilizing an anthropological book by [[Paula Gustafson]] and by examining blankets handed down in their family and in museums in BC, Washington and New York.<ref name=\":2\" /> Says Sparrow of the weaving process: \"And when I stand \u2013 in front of my loom and I\u2019m working and creating, I\u2019m with them, I\u2019m not here anymore. I\u2019m back in time and I\u2019m thinking of the women and they\u2019re whispering to me and guiding me\".<ref>Musqueam Education Centre. Vancouver, BC.</ref> Although the weavers are not able to access the dog hair originally utilized by Salish weavers, due to the extinction of the animals,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Shore to Shore: The Work of Luke Tsu ts'u mult Marston|last=Fournier|first=Suzanne|publisher=Harbour Publishing|year=2014|isbn=|location=Madiera Park, BC|pages=}}</ref><ref>Barsh, Russel L., Joan Megan Jones, and Wayne Shuttles. \"History, Ethnography, and Archaeology of the Coast Salish Woolly-Dog.\" ''Dogs and People in Social, Working, Economic or Symbolic Interaction'' (eds Lynn M. Snyder and Elizabeth A. Moore) pp. 1\u201311. 9th Conference of the International Council of Archaeozoology: Durham, 2002. http://www.kwiaht.org/images/terrbiodiversity/Coast%20Salish%20woolly%20dogs%20as%20published.pdf</ref> sheep's wool, often hand spun, has made the transition into the weaving technique. The weaving is time intensive: \"Robes take longer to weave than totem poles take to carve\".<ref>United States Consulate General in Vancovuer. ''First Nations Weaving Revival Exhibit''. ''U.S. Embassy & Consulates in Canada''. N.p., 17 July 2010. Web. 13 Feb. 2016. http://vancouver.usconsulate.gov/news-events/2010-news-and-events/17-july-2010-first-nations-weaving-revival-exhibit.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214191954/http://vancouver.usconsulate.gov/news-events/2010-news-and-events/17-july-2010-first-nations-weaving-revival-exhibit.html |date=2013-02-14 }}</ref>\n\n== Educating others ==\nSparrow is active in the education community at various levels. She has designed programs and taught elementary aged children about Musqueam culture and history, through the [[Museum of Anthropology at UBC|UBC Museum of Anthropology]].<ref>''Museum of Anthropology of University of British Columbia Annual Report''. Rep. Vancouver: MOA UBC, 2005-6. Print. 23 March 2016. http://moa.ubc.ca/wp-content/uploads/MOA-Annual-Report-2005-2006.pdf</ref> She teaches Salish weaving techniques to children, teenagers and adults: taught at Birkland Brothers Wool Shop, through the Urban Weavers project, through MOA and the Vancouver School Board.<ref>\"About.\" ''The Urban Weaver Project''. N.p., 17 Mar. 2012. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. https://theurbanweaverproject.wordpress.com/about-2/</ref>\n\nSparrow gives demonstrations and public talks at venues such as the Greater Vancouver Weavers and Spinners Guild <ref>Ryeburn, Jo Anne. \"Program \u2013 Debra Sparrow.\" ''Greater Vancouver Weavers Spinners Guild''. N.p., 19 Apr. 2007. Web. 23 Mar. 2016. http://www.gvwsg.com/2007/04/debra-sparrow/</ref> and the [[Bill Reid]] Gallery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billreidgallery.ca/Programs/PublicPrograms.php|title=The Power of Weaving|last=|first=|date=6 November 2010|website=Bill Reid Gallery - Public Programs|publisher=|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> She also participates in presentations and publications with national and international symposia and conferences in regards to indigenous modern and traditional art, such as [[UNESCO]]<ref>\"Symposium on \"Indigenous Identities: Oral, Written Expressions and New Technologies\"\" (n.d.): n. pag. 15 Mar. 2001. Web. 12 Mar. 2016. http://portal.unesco.org/culture/en/files/36904/12075601861Symposium.pdf/Symposium.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203054557/http://portal.unesco.org/culture/en/files/36904/12075601861Symposium.pdf/Symposium.pdf |date=2008-12-03 }}</ref> and the European Textile Network.<ref>\" Textile Forum Service.\" ''Textile Forum Magazine''. N.p., Apr. 1994. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. http://www.tfs-etn.com/shop/magazines/1994_4e.php</ref>\n\nSparrow has been an instructor at [[Langara College]] during their Fall and Winter 2018/19 semesters teaching a Reconciliation Weaving course as a continuation of the college's previous Reconciliation Carving series instructed by [[Squamish people|Squamish]] artist [[Aaron Nelson-Moody]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.langaravoice.ca/reconciliation-carving-series-at-langara-college-focuses-on-building-traditions/|title=Reconciliation Carving Series at Langara College focuses on building traditions|last=Lee La Madeleine|first=Bonnie|date=October 17, 2016|website=Langara Voice}}</ref> \n\n== Major works ==\nSparrow's work is sought by private and public collections including the [[University of British Columbia]], [[Heard Museum]] in Phoenix, Arizona; the [[Canadian Museum of History|Canadian Museum of Civilization]] in Hull, Quebec; the [[Royal British Columbia Museum|Royal B.C. Museum]] in Victoria; [[Paramount Studios]] in Los Angeles; and the [[Burke Museum of Natural History and Culture]] in Seattle, WA.\n\nIn 1996 Sparrow and her sister Robyn wove two blankets of four in the \"Out of the Silence\" installation at the [[Vancouver International Airport]]. The four weavings are made from hand-dyed, hand spun sheep's wool and measure 4.9 x 1.5 meters each. The other artists are Krista Point, Gina Grant and Helen Calbreath.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">\"Musqueam Welcome Area.\" ''YVR''. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. http://www.yvr.ca/en/about-yvr/art/musqueam-welcome-area</ref> The weavings are part of the [http://www.yvr.ca/en/about-yvr/art/musqueam-welcome-area Musqueam Welcome Area] of the International Arrivals area, the official welcoming area to Canada, British Columbia and Vancouver for all international flights, along with carvings by [[Susan Point]] of ''Welcoming Figures'' and ''Flight (Spinning Whorl)'' <ref name=\":3\" />''.'' One of the blankets woven by Debra and Robyn is titled ''Sulsila'', which translates as \"The Grandparents,\" and was reproduced by the Kanata Blanket Company.<ref>\"Sulsila Wool Blanket.\" ''Boardroom Bespoke RSS''. N.p., n.d. Web. Apr. 2016. http://www.boardroombespoke.com/sulsila-wool-blanket</ref>\n\nOther designs of Sparrow's are reproduced by the Kanata Blanket Company in their Licensed Artist Designs line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanatablanket.com/about-us/|title=About Us \u2013 Kanata Blanket|website=Kanata Blanket|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427135642/http://www.kanatablanket.com/about-us/|archive-date=2016-04-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Sparrow was commissioned to create a ceremonial blanket and shawl for the First Nations gallery at [[Government House (British Columbia)|Government House]] in Victoria, BC.<ref>First Peoples\u2019 Cultural Council. \"Debra Sparrow Honoured at Government House.\" Online video clip. YouTube. YouTube, 29 Sept. 2009. Web. 16 Feb. 2016. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mg-4wP0F9_c</ref>\n\nSparrow designed the logo for the Canadian Hockey Teams for the [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games]] in Vancouver, BC.<ref>\"New Olympic Hockey Jerseys Feature First Nation Design.\" ''CBCnews''. CBC/Radio Canada, 17 Aug. 2009. Web. 19 Feb. 2016. http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/new-olympic-hockey-jerseys-feature-first-nation-design-1.844061</ref> The maple leaf shaped logo features a collage of Salish and Canadian symbols drawn by Sparrow including thunderbird, eagle, beaver, moose, hockey sticks, fleur de lis, Orcas, hockey players and maple leaves. Sparrow worked in conjunction with Stuart Iwasaki, graphic designer for [[Nike, Inc.|Nike, Inc]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFor the 2010 Olympic Games, Debra and Robyn Sparrow created two weavings, ''Thunderbirds: Keepers of the Sky,'' which hang in [[UBC Thunderbird Arena]]. These are permanent pieces that remain in the venue as a legacy of the Games.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSparrow was part of the design team that created the Queen of the Night costume in [[Vancouver Opera]]\u2019s Coastal Salish inspired production of [[The Magic Flute]] in 2013.<ref>Vancouver Opera. ''The Magic Flute''. ''Vancouver Opera''. Vancouver Opera, 4 Feb. 2013. Press Release, Web. 20 Feb. 2016. https://www.vancouveropera.ca/sites/default/files/MagicFlute-Feb2013-FINAL1.pdf</ref> She was also commissioned by [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] to create regalia for the movie ''[[White Fang 2: Myth of the White Wolf|White Fang II]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://debrasparrow.ca/sparrow_resume.pdf|title=Sparrow Resume|last=Sparrow|first=Debra|date=2008|website=|publisher=|access-date=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Sparrow, in conjunction with Vancouver-based company Peau de Loup, designed the ''Unity Scarf'' for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 FIFA Women\u2019s World Cup]]. The ''Unity Scarf'' was a double-sided printed with a Salish design on one side and the word Canada on the other. Sparrow said \"\"I am honoured to share these intricate designs with Peau de Loup for the National Women\u2019s team so that the world has an opportunity to see the relationship between all the people in Canada\u2026 I hold my hands up to all Women Athletes who have come to compete at the world level\u2026 Welcome!\" of the work and the accomplishments of women athletes.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018 Sparrow undertook several mural projects across the city of Vancouver. In collaboration with the Vancouver Mural Festival, Sparrow will be designing a three part mural series titled ''\"Blanketing the City\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://salishseasentinel.ca/2018/10/blanketing-the-city/|title=Blanketing the city|last=Mckenna|first=Cara|website=Salish Sea Sentinel}}</ref> incorporating contemporary [[Coast Salish art|Coast Salish design]] elements, focusing on geometric blanket weaving patterns. The first Mural in the series was unveiled as the centrepiece of the VMF Art Smash event on [[Granville Island]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/arts/1074566/photos-first-look-murals-created-art-smash-granville-island|title=A first look at the murals created for Art Smash at Granville Island|last=Kwan|first=Tammy|date=May 11, 2018|website=The Georgia Straight}}</ref>. The mural is a wrap around design over two cement pillars underneath the [[Granville Street Bridge]]. ''<nowiki/>'\"Blanketing the City Pt. II\"'' is located in the [[Mount Pleasant, Vancouver|Mount Pleasant]] neighbourhood and the third mural is in collaboration with [[Capilano University]] and [[Sto:lo]] artist Carrielynn Victor as a part of the schools 50th anniversary celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capilanou.ca/about-capu/get-to-know-us/news/2018/title-65737-en.php|title=Mural artists selected to beautify Capilano University|last=Rossi|first=Cheryl|date=August 17, 2018|website=Capilano University}}</ref> As a part of the 2018 SKOOKUM music festival, Sparrow contributed a pop up mural installation as a part of the festivals \"SKOOKUM After Dark\" events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/music/1119751/skookum-after-dark-festival-widens-its-scope-post-park-concert-series|title=SKOOKUM After Dark: Festival widens its scope with post-park concert series|last=Kwan|first=Tammy|date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Publications by Debra Sparrow ==\n\n* {{Cite book|last1=Musqueam Museum School Programme|title=Musqueam Museum School: the academics of art and culture, teaching and resource guide|last2=Sparrow|first2=Debra|last3=Point|first3=Rose|last4=Baird|first4=Jill Rachel|last5=Musqueam Indian Band|last6=University of British Columbia|last7=Museum of Anthropology|date=2002|publisher=UBC Museum of Anthropology|year=|isbn=|location=Vancouver|pages=|oclc=606952634}}\n* ''Weaving Worlds Together'' by Debra Sparrow and Jill Baird, presented at the Symposium on \"Indigenous Identities: Oral, Written Expressions and New Technologies.\" UNESCO, 2001.\n* \"Know who you are, Know where you come from\" in ''A Hurricane in the Basement.'' City of Vancouver, 2000.\n* {{Cite book|last=Sparrow|first=Debra|url=http://worldcat.org/search?q=on:CAXTE+http://e-artexte.ca/cgi/oai2+DCG_ENTIRE_REPOSITORY+CNTCOLL|title=Material Matters: The Art and Culture of Contemporary Textiles|publisher=YYZ Books|year=1998|isbn=|editor-last=Bachmann|editor-first=Ingrid|location=Toronto|pages=|chapter=A Journey|oclc=948713036|accessdate=2020-04-19|editor-last2=Scheuing|editor-first2=Ruth}} \n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/search?q=on:CAXTE+http://e-artexte.ca/cgi/oai2+DCG_ENTIRE_REPOSITORY+CNTCOLL|title=Topographies: Aspects of Recent B.C. Art|date=1996|publisher=Vancouver Art Gallery|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|oclc=948713170|accessdate=2020-04-19}}\n* \"Out of the Silence\" in ''European Textile Network December 1994,'' pp 43\u201345.\n* 1995\u20131997  Debra Sparrow  Weaving Two Worlds Together ''School Programme at the UBC Museum of Anthropology'' Vancouver\n\n== Awards ==\nBC Creative Achievement Award for First Nations' Art, 2008 <ref>\"Native Artists to Receive Provincial Award.\" ''The Globe and Mail''. N.p., 14 May 2008. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/native-artists-to-receive-provincial-award/article672365/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://debrasparrow.ca/}}\n* [http://www.musqueam.bc.ca/ Musqueam website]\n* [http://moa.ubc.ca/ UBC Museum of Anthropology website]\n\n<!--\n, \n, \n, \n,\n-->\n\n{{authority control|VIAF=309816783|ISNI=0000000464133320}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sparrow, Debra}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Northwest Coast art]]\n[[Category:Canadian women artists]]\n[[Category:Coast Salish people]]\n[[Category:First Nations women]]\n[[Category:Artists from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:First Nations textile artists]]\n[[Category:Canadian textile artists]]\n[[Category:Women textile artists]]\n[[Category:Langara College people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Debra Sparrow''', or \u03b8\u0259li\u03c7\u02b7\u0259l\u02b7\u0259t (Thelliawhatlwit), is a Musqueam weaver, artist and knowledge keeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aboriginal.ubc.ca/2014/07/03/new-ubc-president-welcomed-and-honored-by-first-nations/|title=Musqueam welcomes President Gupta on his first day {{!}} Aboriginal Portal|last=Ward|first=Kevin|website=aboriginal.ubc.ca|access-date=2016-04-18}}</ref> She is self-taught in Salish design, weaving, and jewellery making.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vancitybuzz.com/2015/05/peau-de-loup-scarf-fifa-womens-world-cup/|title=Vancouver Brand Peau De Loup Designs Scarf for 2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|last=Kwon|first=Crystal|date=18 May 2015|work=Vancity Buzz|access-date=18 February 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nSparrow was born and raised on the [[Musqueam Indian Band|Musqueam Indian]] Reserve, part of the traditional territories of the Musqueam people, in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]. Sparrow credits her grandfather, Ed Sparrow, who lived to be 100 years old and remembered the forcible removal of the Musqueam people from [[Stanley Park]], with giving her \"300 years of stories\" that grounded her in her heritage and enabled her to hear the voices of her ancestors. \"We never stopped dancing, we never stopped singing, we never stopped practising our cultural ways,\" says Sparrow, who considers herself a person who lives and practises traditional ways.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gallerieswest.ca/blogs-and-buzz/%22coast-salish-revival%22%3A-timeless%2C-elegant-art-thrives-thanks/|title=\"Coast Salish Revival\": Timeless, elegant art thrives thanks to visionaries like Simon Charlie|last=Fournier|first=Suzanne|date=23 May 2015|website=Galleries West|publisher=|access-date=12 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nSparrow is the mother of three grown children.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/but-wheres-the-loonie/article428248|title=But Where's the Loonie?|last=Sekeres|first=Matthew|date=18 August 2009|website=The Globe and Mail|publisher=|access-date=18 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Musqueam Weavers ==\nBy the time of Sparrow's childhood the techniques of [[Salish weaving]] were lost to the Musqueam nation. There were no living weavers to teach a new generation; the last known weaver before the revival was Sparrow's great grandmother.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://199.243.64.45/musqueam-sisters-revive-traditional-salish-weaving |title=Musqueam Sisters Revive Traditional Salish Weaving |last= |first= |date=20 November 2009 |website=Four Host Nations |publisher= |access-date=23 February 2016 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 1985, Wendy John, Sparrow's eldest sister attended a Salish weaving course at the Vancouver Indian Centre (now the [http://www.vafcs.org/ Vancouver Aboriginal Friendship Centre]). The next year, Sparrow and her younger sister Robyn Sparrow began to study weaving as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=891e7a18-78ee-499b-aab9-0f65938c1e78 |title=Aboriginal Heroes: Spinning a Cloth through Time |last=Griffith |first=Kevin |date=20 June 2008 |website=Canada.com |publisher=CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc. |access-date=20 February 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611062844/http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=891e7a18-78ee-499b-aab9-0f65938c1e78 |archivedate=11 June 2016 }}</ref>\n\nAlong with her sister Robyn, Sparrow co-founded a group of women weavers in the 1980s who rejuvenated the Salish Weaving tradition.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Musqueam Weavers Source Book|last=Baird|first=Jill Rachel|last2=Johnson|first2=Elizabeth Lominska|publisher=Museum of Anthropology at University of British Columbia|year=2002|isbn=|location=Vancouver, BC|pages=}}</ref> They were able to reconstruct the lost weaving techniques utilizing an anthropological book by [[Paula Gustafson]] and by examining blankets handed down in their family and in museums in BC, Washington and New York.<ref name=\":2\" /> Says Sparrow of the weaving process: \"And when I stand \u2013 in front of my loom and I\u2019m working and creating, I\u2019m with them, I\u2019m not here anymore. I\u2019m back in time and I\u2019m thinking of the women and they\u2019re whispering to me and guiding me\".<ref>Musqueam Education Centre. Vancouver, BC.</ref> Although the weavers are not able to access the dog hair originally utilized by Salish weavers, due to the extinction of the animals,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Shore to Shore: The Work of Luke Tsu ts'u mult Marston|last=Fournier|first=Suzanne|publisher=Harbour Publishing|year=2014|isbn=|location=Madiera Park, BC|pages=}}</ref><ref>Barsh, Russel L., Joan Megan Jones, and Wayne Shuttles. \"History, Ethnography, and Archaeology of the Coast Salish Woolly-Dog.\" ''Dogs and People in Social, Working, Economic or Symbolic Interaction'' (eds Lynn M. Snyder and Elizabeth A. Moore) pp. 1\u201311. 9th Conference of the International Council of Archaeozoology: Durham, 2002. http://www.kwiaht.org/images/terrbiodiversity/Coast%20Salish%20woolly%20dogs%20as%20published.pdf</ref> sheep's wool, often hand spun, has made the transition into the weaving technique. The weaving is time intensive: \"Robes take longer to weave than totem poles take to carve\".<ref>United States Consulate General in Vancovuer. ''First Nations Weaving Revival Exhibit''. ''U.S. Embassy & Consulates in Canada''. N.p., 17 July 2010. Web. 13 Feb. 2016. http://vancouver.usconsulate.gov/news-events/2010-news-and-events/17-july-2010-first-nations-weaving-revival-exhibit.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214191954/http://vancouver.usconsulate.gov/news-events/2010-news-and-events/17-july-2010-first-nations-weaving-revival-exhibit.html |date=2013-02-14 }}</ref>\n\n== Educating others ==\nSparrow is active in the education community at various levels. She has designed programs and taught elementary aged children about Musqueam culture and history, through the [[Museum of Anthropology at UBC|UBC Museum of Anthropology]].<ref>''Museum of Anthropology of University of British Columbia Annual Report''. Rep. Vancouver: MOA UBC, 2005-6. Print. 23 March 2016. http://moa.ubc.ca/wp-content/uploads/MOA-Annual-Report-2005-2006.pdf</ref> She teaches Salish weaving techniques to children, teenagers and adults: taught at Birkland Brothers Wool Shop, through the Urban Weavers project, through MOA and the Vancouver School Board.<ref>\"About.\" ''The Urban Weaver Project''. N.p., 17 Mar. 2012. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. https://theurbanweaverproject.wordpress.com/about-2/</ref>\n\nSparrow gives demonstrations and public talks at venues such as the Greater Vancouver Weavers and Spinners Guild <ref>Ryeburn, Jo Anne. \"Program \u2013 Debra Sparrow.\" ''Greater Vancouver Weavers Spinners Guild''. N.p., 19 Apr. 2007. Web. 23 Mar. 2016. http://www.gvwsg.com/2007/04/debra-sparrow/</ref> and the [[Bill Reid]] Gallery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billreidgallery.ca/Programs/PublicPrograms.php|title=The Power of Weaving|last=|first=|date=6 November 2010|website=Bill Reid Gallery - Public Programs|publisher=|access-date=2 April 2016}}</ref> She also participates in presentations and publications with national and international symposia and conferences in regards to indigenous modern and traditional art, such as [[UNESCO]]<ref>\"Symposium on \"Indigenous Identities: Oral, Written Expressions and New Technologies\"\" (n.d.): n. pag. 15 Mar. 2001. Web. 12 Mar. 2016. http://portal.unesco.org/culture/en/files/36904/12075601861Symposium.pdf/Symposium.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203054557/http://portal.unesco.org/culture/en/files/36904/12075601861Symposium.pdf/Symposium.pdf |date=2008-12-03 }}</ref> and the European Textile Network.<ref>\" Textile Forum Service.\" ''Textile Forum Magazine''. N.p., Apr. 1994. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. http://www.tfs-etn.com/shop/magazines/1994_4e.php</ref>\n\nSparrow has been an instructor at [[Langara College]] during their Fall and Winter 2018/19 semesters teaching a Reconciliation Weaving course as a continuation of the college's previous Reconciliation Carving series instructed by [[Squamish people|Squamish]] artist [[Aaron Nelson-Moody]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.langaravoice.ca/reconciliation-carving-series-at-langara-college-focuses-on-building-traditions/|title=Reconciliation Carving Series at Langara College focuses on building traditions|last=Lee La Madeleine|first=Bonnie|date=October 17, 2016|website=Langara Voice}}</ref> \n\n== Major Works ==\nSparrow's work is sought by private and public collections including the [[University of British Columbia]], [[Heard Museum]] in Phoenix, Arizona; the [[Canadian Museum of History|Canadian Museum of Civilization]] in Hull, Quebec; the [[Royal British Columbia Museum|Royal B.C. Museum]] in Victoria; [[Paramount Studios]] in Los Angeles; and the [[Burke Museum of Natural History and Culture]] in Seattle, WA.\n\nIn 1996 Sparrow and her sister Robyn wove two blankets of four in the \"Out of the Silence\" installation at the [[Vancouver International Airport]]. The four weavings are made from hand-dyed, hand spun sheep's wool and measure 4.9 x 1.5 meters each. The other artists are Krista Point, Gina Grant and Helen Calbreath.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\">\"Musqueam Welcome Area.\" ''YVR''. N.p., n.d. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. http://www.yvr.ca/en/about-yvr/art/musqueam-welcome-area</ref> The weavings are part of the [http://www.yvr.ca/en/about-yvr/art/musqueam-welcome-area Musqueam Welcome Area] of the International Arrivals area, the official welcoming area to Canada, British Columbia and Vancouver for all international flights, along with carvings by [[Susan Point]] of ''Welcoming Figures'' and ''Flight (Spinning Whorl)'' <ref name=\":3\" />''.'' One of the blankets woven by Debra and Robyn is titled ''Sulsila'', which translates as \"The Grandparents,\" and was reproduced by the Kanata Blanket Company.<ref>\"Sulsila Wool Blanket.\" ''Boardroom Bespoke RSS''. N.p., n.d. Web. Apr. 2016. http://www.boardroombespoke.com/sulsila-wool-blanket</ref>\n\nOther designs of Sparrow's are reproduced by the Kanata Blanket Company in their Licensed Artist Designs line.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kanatablanket.com/about-us/|title=About Us - Kanata Blanket|website=Kanata Blanket|language=en-US|access-date=2016-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427135642/http://www.kanatablanket.com/about-us/|archive-date=2016-04-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Sparrow was commissioned to create a ceremonial blanket and shawl for the First Nations gallery at [[Government House (British Columbia)|Government House]] in Victoria, BC.<ref>First Peoples\u2019 Cultural Council. \"Debra Sparrow Honoured at Government House.\" Online video clip. YouTube. YouTube, 29 Sept. 2009. Web. 16 Feb. 2016. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Mg-4wP0F9_c</ref>\n\nSparrow designed the logo for the Canadian Hockey Teams for the [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Olympic and Paralympic Winter Games]] in Vancouver, BC.<ref>\"New Olympic Hockey Jerseys Feature First Nation Design.\" ''CBCnews''. CBC/Radio Canada, 17 Aug. 2009. Web. 19 Feb. 2016. http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/new-olympic-hockey-jerseys-feature-first-nation-design-1.844061</ref> The maple leaf shaped logo features a collage of Salish and Canadian symbols drawn by Sparrow including thunderbird, eagle, beaver, moose, hockey sticks, fleur de lis, Orcas, hockey players and maple leaves. Sparrow worked in conjunction with Stuart Iwasaki, graphic designer for [[Nike, Inc.|Nike, Inc]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFor the 2010 Olympic Games, Debra and Robyn Sparrow created two weavings, ''Thunderbirds: Keepers of the Sky,'' which hang in [[UBC Thunderbird Arena]]. These are permanent pieces that remain in the venue as a legacy of the Games.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nSparrow was part of the design team that created the Queen of the Night costume in [[Vancouver Opera]]\u2019s Coastal Salish inspired production of [[The Magic Flute]] in 2013.<ref>Vancouver Opera. ''The Magic Flute''. ''Vancouver Opera''. Vancouver Opera, 4 Feb. 2013. Press Release, Web. 20 Feb. 2016. https://www.vancouveropera.ca/sites/default/files/MagicFlute-Feb2013-FINAL1.pdf</ref> She was also commissioned by [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] to create regalia for the movie ''[[White Fang 2: Myth of the White Wolf|White Fang II]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://debrasparrow.ca/sparrow_resume.pdf|title=Sparrow Resume|last=Sparrow|first=Debra|date=2008|website=|publisher=|access-date=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 Sparrow, in conjunction with Vancouver-based company Peau de Loup, designed the ''Unity Scarf'' for the [[2015 FIFA Women's World Cup|2015 FIFA Women\u2019s World Cup]]. The ''Unity Scarf'' was a double-sided printed with a Salish design on one side and the word Canada on the other. Sparrow said \"\"I am honoured to share these intricate designs with Peau de Loup for the National Women\u2019s team so that the world has an opportunity to see the relationship between all the people in Canada\u2026 I hold my hands up to all Women Athletes who have come to compete at the world level\u2026 Welcome!\" of the work and the accomplishments of women athletes.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2018 Sparrow undertook several mural projects across the city of Vancouver. In collaboration with the Vancouver Mural Festival, Sparrow will be designing a three part mural series titled ''\"Blanketing the City\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://salishseasentinel.ca/2018/10/blanketing-the-city/|title=Blanketing the city|last=Mckenna|first=Cara|website=Salish Sea Sentinel}}</ref> incorporating contemporary [[Coast Salish art|Coast Salish design]] elements, focusing on geometric blanket weaving patterns. The first Mural in the series was unveiled as the centrepiece of the VMF Art Smash event on [[Granville Island]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/arts/1074566/photos-first-look-murals-created-art-smash-granville-island|title=A first look at the murals created for Art Smash at Granville Island|last=Kwan|first=Tammy|date=May 11, 2018|website=The Georgia Straight}}</ref>. The mural is a wrap around design over two cement pillars underneath the [[Granville Street Bridge]]. ''<nowiki/>'\"Blanketing the City Pt. II\"'' is located in the [[Mount Pleasant, Vancouver|Mount Pleasant]] neighbourhood and the third mural is in collaboration with [[Capilano University]] and [[Sto:lo]] artist Carrielynn Victor as a part of the schools 50th anniversary celebrations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capilanou.ca/about-capu/get-to-know-us/news/2018/title-65737-en.php|title=Mural artists selected to beautify Capilano University|last=Rossi|first=Cheryl|date=August 17, 2018|website=Capilano University}}</ref> As a part of the 2018 SKOOKUM music festival, Sparrow contributed a pop up mural installation as a part of the festivals \"SKOOKUM After Dark\" events<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straight.com/music/1119751/skookum-after-dark-festival-widens-its-scope-post-park-concert-series|title=SKOOKUM After Dark: Festival widens its scope with post-park concert series|last=Kwan|first=Tammy|date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Publications by Debra Sparrow ==\n\n* {{Cite book|last1=Musqueam Museum School Programme|title=Musqueam Museum School: the academics of art and culture, teaching and resource guide|last2=Sparrow|first2=Debra|last3=Point|first3=Rose|last4=Baird|first4=Jill Rachel|last5=Musqueam Indian Band|last6=University of British Columbia|last7=Museum of Anthropology|date=2002|publisher=UBC Museum of Anthropology|year=|isbn=|location=Vancouver|pages=|oclc=606952634}}\n* ''Weaving Worlds Together'' by Debra Sparrow and Jill Baird, presented at the Symposium on \"Indigenous Identities: Oral, Written Expressions and New Technologies.\" UNESCO, 2001.\n* \"Know who you are, Know where you come from\" in ''A Hurricane in the Basement.'' City of Vancouver, 2000.\n* {{Cite book|last=Sparrow|first=Debra|url=http://worldcat.org/search?q=on:CAXTE+http://e-artexte.ca/cgi/oai2+DCG_ENTIRE_REPOSITORY+CNTCOLL|title=Material Matters: The Art and Culture of Contemporary Textiles|publisher=YYZ Books|year=1998|isbn=|editor-last=Bachmann|editor-first=Ingrid|location=Toronto|pages=|chapter=A Journey|oclc=948713036|accessdate=2020-04-19|editor-last2=Scheuing|editor-first2=Ruth}} \n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://worldcat.org/search?q=on:CAXTE+http://e-artexte.ca/cgi/oai2+DCG_ENTIRE_REPOSITORY+CNTCOLL|title=Topographies: Aspects of Recent B.C. Art|date=1996|publisher=Vancouver Art Gallery|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|oclc=948713170|accessdate=2020-04-19}}\n* \"Out of the Silence\" in ''European Textile Network December 1994,'' pp 43\u201345.\n* 1995 \u2013 1997  Debra Sparrow  Weaving Two Worlds Together ''School Programme at the UBC Museum of Anthropology'' Vancouver\n\n== Awards ==\nBC Creative Achievement Award for First Nations' Art, 2008 <ref>\"Native Artists to Receive Provincial Award.\" ''The Globe and Mail''. N.p., 14 May 2008. Web. 18 Mar. 2016. https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/native-artists-to-receive-provincial-award/article672365/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://debrasparrow.ca/}}\n* [http://www.musqueam.bc.ca/ Musqueam website]\n* [http://moa.ubc.ca/ UBC Museum of Anthropology website]\n\n<!--\n, \n, \n, \n,\n-->\n\n{{authority control|VIAF=309816783|ISNI=0000000464133320}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sparrow, Debra}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Northwest Coast art]]\n[[Category:Canadian women artists]]\n[[Category:Coast Salish people]]\n[[Category:First Nations women]]\n[[Category:Artists from British Columbia]]\n[[Category:First Nations textile artists]]\n[[Category:Canadian textile artists]]\n[[Category:Women textile artists]]\n[[Category:Langara College people]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: -  \u2192  \u2013 , 1995 \u2013 1997 \u2192 1995\u20131997, Works \u2192 works, etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debra_Sparrow"}
{"title_page": "Corporate debt bubble", "text_new": "{{short description|Mass acquisition of low-quality corporate bonds by investors in the late 2010s and 2020}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2020}}\nThe \"'''corporate debt bubble'''\" refers to the large increase in [[corporate bonds]], excluding that of [[financial institution]]s, following the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]]. Global corporate debt rose from 84% of [[gross world product]] in 2009 to 92% in 2019, or about $72 trillion.<ref name=\"Economist_120420\">{{cite web |title=Corporate bonds and loans are at the centre of a new financial scare |url=https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2020/03/12/corporate-bonds-and-loans-are-at-the-centre-of-a-new-financial-scare |website=The Economist |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IIF_070420\">{{cite web |title=April 2020 Global Debt Monitor: COVID-19 Lights a Fuse |url=https://www.iif.com/Publications/ID/3839/April-2020-Global-Debt-Monitor-COVID-19-Lights-a-Fuse |website=Institute of International Finance |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> In the world's eight largest economies - [[China]], the [[United States]], [[Japan]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[France]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], and [[Germany]] - total corporate debt was about $51 trillion in 2019, compared to $34 trillion in 2009.<ref name=\"IMF_161019\">{{cite web |title=Transcript of October 2019 Global Financial Stability Report Press Briefing |url=https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2019/10/16/tr101619-transcript-of-press-conference-on-release-of-october-2019-global-financial-stability-report |website=International Monetary Fund |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Excluding debt held by [[financial institution]]s - which trade debt as [[mortgage]]s, [[student loan]]s, etc - the debt owed by non-financial companies in early March 2020 was $13 trillion worldwide, of which about $9.6 trillion was in the U.S.<ref name=\"AP_120320\">{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Paul |last2=Condon |first2=Bernard |last3=Bussewitz |first3=Cathy |title=Corporate debt loads a rising risk as virus hits economy |url=https://apnews.com/7cd0108d79c6b4f1ee2e6ec5fc3a2275 |website=AP News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe corporate bond market historically centered in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\">{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Susan |title=Are we in a corporate debt bubble? |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/overview/in-the-news/are-we-in-a-corporate-debt-bubble |website=McKinsey Global Institute |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> The [[U.S. Federal Reserve]] noted in November 2019 that [[leveraged loan]]s, corporate bonds made to companies with poor credit histories or large amounts of existing debt, were the fastest growing asset class, increasing in size by 14.6% in 2018 alone.<ref name=\"Fed_FSR_1109_1\">{{cite web |title=Financial Stability Report - 1. Asset valuation |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/2019-november-financial-stability-report-asset-valuation.htm |website=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=November 2019}}</ref> Total U.S. corporate debt in November 2019 reached a record 47% of the [[Economy of the United States|entire U.S. economy]].<ref name=WaPo_291119>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |title=Corporate debt nears a record $10 trillion, and borrowing binge poses new risks |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/corporate-debt-nears-a-record-10-trillion-and-borrowing-binge-poses-new-risks/2019/11/29/1f86ba3e-114b-11ea-bf62-eadd5d11f559_story.html |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\">{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Susan |title=Are we in a corporate debt bubble? |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/overview/in-the-news/are-we-in-a-corporate-debt-bubble |website=McKinsey Global Institute |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> However, corporate borrowing expanded worldwide under the low [[interest rate]]s of the [[Great Recession]]. Two-thirds of global growth in corporate debt occurred in [[developing country|developing countries]], in particular [[Economy of China|China]]. The value of outstanding Chinese non-financial corporate bonds increased from $69 billion in 2007 to $2 trillion in 2017.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> In December 2019, [[Moody's Analytics]] described Chinese corporate debt as the \"biggest threat\" to the global economy.<ref name=CNBC_171219>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Weizhen |title=Chinese corporate debt is the 'biggest threat' to the global economy, says Moody's chief economist |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/17/chinas-corporate-debt-is-biggest-threat-to-global-economy-moodys.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nRegulators and investors have raised concern that large amounts of risky corporate debt have created a critical vulnerability for financial markets, in particular [[mutual funds]], during the next [[recession]].<ref name=WaPo_291119/> Former Fed Chair [[Janet Yellen]] has warned that the large amount of corporate debt could \"prolong\" the next recession and cause corporate bankruptcies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kolakowski |first1=Mark |title=Why The Corporate Debt Bubble May Burst Sooner Than You Think |url=https://www.investopedia.com/why-the-corporate-debt-bubble-may-burst-sooner-than-you-think-4587446 |website=Investopedia |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=20 February 2019}}</ref> The [[Institute of International Finance]] forecast that, in an economic downturn half as severe as the 2008 crisis,  $19 trillion in debt would be owed by non-financial firms without the earnings to cover the interest payments, referred to as [[zombie company|zombie firms]].<ref name=\"IMF_161019\"/> The [[McKinsey Global Institute]] warned in 2018 that the greatest risks would be to [[emerging market]]s such as China, [[India]], and [[Brazil]], where 25-30% of bonds had been issued by high-risk companies.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/>\n\n==Low bond yields led to purchase of riskier bonds==\n[[File:US corporate bonds held by mutual funds 2001-2019.svg|thumb|right|300px|The amount of US corporate bonds held by [[mutual fund]]s tripled in the decade following the financial crisis of 2007\u201308.]]\nFollowing the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]], the [[Federal Reserve Board]] lowered short- and long-term interest rates in order to convince investors to move out of interest-bearing assets and match with borrowers seeking capital. The resulting [[market liquidity]] was accomplished through two steps: cutting the [[Fed Funds]] rate, the rate that the Fed charges institutional investors to borrow money; and [[quantitative easing]], whereby the Fed buying trillions of dollars of [[toxic asset]]s, effectively creating functioning markets for these assets and reassuring investors. The success of the U.S. Fed in dropping interest rates to historically low levels and preventing illiquid markets from worsening the financial crisis prompted [[central bank]]s around the world to copy these techniques.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\">{{cite web |last1=Cohan |first1=William D. |title=The Big, Dangerous Bubble in Corporate Debt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/opinion/corporate-debt-bubble-next-recession.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=9 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Alster |first1=Norm |title=Companies With High Debt Are Paying a Price |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/business/high-debt-companies-investing.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the effect of quantitative easing was not limited to the toxic [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage bonds]] targeted by central banks, as it effectively reduced the supply of [[Bond (finance)|bond]]s as a class, causing prices for bonds generally to rise and bond [[Yield (finance)|yields]] to lower. For over a decade, the artificially low interest rates and artificially low bond yields, have caused a \"mispricing of risk\" as investors continually seek out higher yields. As an example, [[high-yield debt]], colloquially known as \"junk bonds,\" has historically yielded 10% or more to compensate investors for the increased risk; in February 2020, the U.S. yield on these bonds dipped to nearly 5%.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=ICE BofA US High Yield Master II Effective Yield |url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/BAMLH0A0HYM2EY |website=Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> This indicates that investors flocking to higher yield have bought so much high-yield debt that it has driven the yield below the level needed to compensate for the risk.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/> U.S. corporate bonds held by mutual funds had tripled over the previous decade.<ref name=\"Fed_FSR_1109_4\">{{cite web |title=Financial Stability Report - 4. Funding risk |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/2019-november-financial-stability-report-funding.htm |website=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, 22% of outstanding U.S. nonfinancial corporate debt was rated \"junk\", and a further 40% was rated one step above junk at \"BBB,\" so that approximately two-thirds of all corporate debt was from companies at the highest risk of default, in particular retailers who were losing business to online services.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> The U.S. Fed noted in November 2019 that mutual funds held about one-sixth of outstanding corporate debt, but were acquiring one-fifth of new leveraged corporate loans. The size of high-yield corporate bond mutual funds, which specialize in riskier bonds, had doubled in the decade prior to 2019.<ref name=\"Fed_FSR_1109_4\"/>\n\nWhile trade in corporate bonds typically centered in the U.S., two-thirds of corporate debt growth since 2007 was in developing countries. China became one of the largest corporate bond markets in the world, with the value of Chinese corporate bonds increasing from $69 billion in 2007 to $2 trillion at the end of 2017.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> By mid-2018, total outstanding U.S. corporate debt reached 45% of GDP, which was larger than that seen during the [[dot-com bubble]] and [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=Forbes_290818>{{cite web |last1=Colombo |first1=Jesse |title=The U.S. Is Experiencing A Dangerous Corporate Debt Bubble |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jessecolombo/2018/08/29/the-u-s-is-experiencing-a-dangerous-corporate-debt-bubble/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=29 August 2018}}</ref> Noting negative bond yields in Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and the US in August 2019,  Bloomberg News stated that effectively paying borrowers to borrow is distorting incentives and misallocating resources, concluding that bonds are on a bubble.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Authers |first1=John |title=Bonds Meet the Four Criteria for Defining a Bubble |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-08-13/the-bond-market-is-in-a-bubble-jz9atl25 |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Low interest rates led to increasingly leveraged companies==\n[[File:Corporate Bond Issuance by credit rating, 1995-2019.png|thumb|400px|While issuance of new high-yield (junk) bonds in the US market has been declining since 2012, the issuance of BAA (the lowest rating of \"investment-grade\", including BBB) matched or exceeded high-yield issuance from 2016 through 2019.]]\nCompanies that do not make enough profit to pay off their debts and are only able to survive by repeatedly [[refinancing]] their loans, known as \"[[Zombie company|zombie firms]],\" have been able to turn over their debt because low interest rates increase the willingness of lenders to buy higher yield corporate debt, while the yield they offer on their bonds remains at near-historical lows. In a 2018 study of 14 rich countries, the [[Bank of International Settlements]] stated that [[Zombie company|zombie firms]] increased from 2% of all firms in the 1980s to 12% in 2016.<ref name=WaPo100320>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |title=Fears of corporate debt bomb grow as coronavirus outbreak worsens |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/10/coronavirus-markets-economy-corporate-debt/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> By March 2020, one-sixth of all publicly-traded companies in the U.S. did not make enough profit to cover the interest on their issued debt.<ref name=\"WaPo100320\"/> In developing countries, high-risk bonds were concentrated in particular industries. In China, one-third of bonds issued by industrial companies and 28% of those issued by real-estate companies are at a higher risk of default, defined as having a [[times interest earned]] of 1.5 or less. In Brazil, one-quarter of all corporate bonds at a higher risk of default are in the industrial sector.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> Fitch stated in December 2019 that the majority of Chinese companies listed on A-share markets, namely the [[Shanghai Stock Exchange]] and [[Shenzhen Stock Exchange]], were unable to repay their debt with their operational cash flow and required refinancing.<ref name=Reuters_101219>{{cite web |last1=Zhou |first1=Winni |last2=Galbraith |first2=Andrew |title=China's private firms face record default risk, to stay high in 2020 - Fitch |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/china-markets-default/chinas-private-firms-face-record-default-risk-to-stay-high-in-2020-fitch-idUKL4N28K1YM |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBond investing in Europe closely followed the actions of the [[European Central Bank]], in particular the quantitative easing implemented in response to the [[European debt crisis]]. In June 2016, the ECB began using its corporate sector purchase programme (CSPP), acquiring 10.4 billion euro in non-financial corporate bonds in the first month of operation, with the explicit purpose of ensuring liquidity in the corporate bond market.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The corporate bond market and the ECB\u2019s corporate sector purchase programme |journal=Economic Bulletin |date=4 August 2016 |issue=5/2016 |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/economic-bulletin/html/eb201605.en.html#IDofBox2 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |publisher=European Central Bank |language=en}}</ref> News in mid-2019 that the ECB would restart its asset purchase program pushed the [[iBoxx]] euro corporate bond index, valued at $1.92 trillion, to record highs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Europe's corporate bond market soars on ECB re-entry bets |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ecb-markets-corpbonds/europes-corporate-bond-market-soars-on-ecb-re-entry-bets-idUSKCN1TM0S8 |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=21 June 2019}}</ref> The increased purchases resulted in 42% of European investment-grade corporate debt having a negative yield, as investors effectively paid less risky companies to borrow money.<ref>{{cite web |title=European top-rated corporate debt with negative yield swells to 40% of market - Tradeweb |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/eurozone-bonds-tradeweb/european-top-rated-corporate-debt-with-negative-yield-swells-to-40-of-market-tradeweb-idUSL8N24X3YY |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=1 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]] noted in January 2020 that only two U.S. firms had the highest rating of AAA, [[Johnson & Johnson]] and [[Microsoft]], while there was an increased number of firms at the lowest-end, called BAA (on the Moody's rating scale) or BBB (on the S&P rating scale). Investment-grade firms, those with a rating between AAA and BAA, were more highly leveraged than the high-yield (\"junk\") firms. Observing that investors tend to divest bonds that are downgraded to high-yield, the New York Fed stated, \"In the current corporate debt landscape, with a greater amount outstanding of BAA-rated corporate debt and higher net leverage of investment-grade debt overall, the possibility of a large volume of corporate bond downgrades poses a [[financial stability]] concern.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boyarchenko |first1=Nina |last2=Shachar |first2=Or |title=What\u2019s in A(AA) Credit Rating? |url=https://libertystreeteconomics.newyorkfed.org/2020/01/whats-in-aaa-credit-rating.html |website=Federal Reserve Bank of New York |publisher=Liberty Street Economics blog |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nExamples of leveraged corporate debt transactions include:\n* [[Halliburton]] doubled its corporate debt to $11.5 billion between 2012 and 2020; it sold $1 billion in debt in early March 2020 with the explicit purpose of paying off existing debt and has $3.8 billion in debt payments due through 2026.<ref name=WaPo100320/>\n* [[AT&T]] debt ballooned to $180 billion following its acquisition of [[Time Warner]] in 2016. In 2018, [[Moody's]] declared AT&T to be \"beholden to the health of the capital markets\" because of its reliance on continued credit to service its debt load.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/>\n* [[KKR]] sold about $1.3 billion of cov-lite debt in 2017 to pay for its buyout of [[Unilever]], despite Moody's rating the offer 4.99 on a scale of 1 to 5, with 5 being the riskiest.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/>\n* [[Kraft Heinz]] had its credit rating downgraded to BBB- or \"junk\" in February 2020 due to low earnings expectations and the firm's determination to use available capital to provide [[stock dividend]]s rather than pay down debt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kraft Heinz's credit rating cut to 'junk' by Fitch |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-kraft-heinz-ratings-fitch-idUSKBN20823O |website=Reuters |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 February 2020}}</ref> That month, Kraft Heinz had $22.9 billion in total debt with only $2.3 billion in cash assets.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Rich |title=Kraft Heinz Debt Is Now Junk |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/02/14/kraft-heinz-debt-is-now-junk.aspx |website=The Motley Fool |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:S&P 500 cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio (CAPE), 2000-2020.png|thumb|300px|The S&P 500 [[cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio]] (CAPE) suggest that the index reached an overvaluation not seen since the dot-com bubble in the late 2010s.]]\nCorporations in the United States have used the debt to finance [[share buyback]]s, dividends, and [[mergers & acquisitions]] that boost share price to a greater extent than before. This has been done in place of long-term business investments and expansions.<ref name=Forbes_290818/> The U.S. [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of December 2017]] offered a tax holiday under the logic that firms would use the extra profits to increase investments. Instead, it vastly increased an existing trend towards share buybacks, which increase the value of the remaining publicly traded shares and contributed to the rise of stock market indexes generally.<ref name=\"Forbes_210219\">{{cite web |last1=Knott |first1=Anne Marie |title=Why The Tax Cuts And Jobs Act (TCJA) Led To Buybacks Rather Than Investment |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/annemarieknott/2019/02/21/why-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-tcja-led-to-buybacks-rather-than-investment/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=21 February 2019}}</ref> While the [[S&P 500]] has risen by over 300% from its low in the [[Great Recession]], this rise is driven partly by the selling of corporate debt to purchase stock that becomes more expensive due to the purchases. The [[cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio]] for the S&P 500 indicates it is the most overvalued it has been since the dot-com bubble and is around [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]] valuations.<ref name=Forbes_290818/>\n\nThe McKinsey Global Institute cautioned in 2018 against excessive alarm, noting that if interest rates rose by 2%, less than 10% of bonds issued in all advanced economies would be at higher risk of default, with the percentage falling to less than 5% of European debt, which is largely issued by AAA-rated companies.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/>\n\n==Search for yield results in growth in covenant light bonds==\n{{main|Cov-lite}}\nMost leveraged corporate bonds are \"[[cov-lite]]\", or covenant light, that do not contain the usual protections for purchasers of the debt. In some cases, cov-lite terms may force the purchaser of the debt to buy more debt.<ref name=MarketWatch_200319>{{cite web |last1=Mauldin |first1=John |title=When the U.S. falls into a recession, a credit bubble will explode |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/when-the-us-falls-into-a-recession-a-credit-bubble-will-explode-2019-03-20 |website=MarketWatch |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=20 March 2019}}</ref> By mid-2018, 77.4% of U.S. leveraged corporate loans were cov-lite.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leveraged Loans: Cov-Lite Volume Reaches Yet Another Record High |url=https://www.spglobal.com/marketintelligence/en/news-insights/latest-news-headlines/leveraged-loan-news/leveraged-loans-cov-lite-volume-reaches-yet-another-record-high |website=S&P Global Market Intelligence |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=22 June 2018}}</ref> Investors seeking stronger covenants lost the struggle with companies and [[private equity firm]]s seeking to offload risk to the buyers of their debt. A writer for [[Bloomberg News]] opined in February 2020, \"If and when the credit cycle turns, the aggressive push toward weakening protections virtually ensures that recovery rates will be worse than in 2008. But there's no going back now: The risky debt markets are full of cov-lite deals. Investors either have to acclimate to that reality or get out of high-yield and leveraged loans.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chappatta |first1=Brian |title=The \u2018Cov-Lite\u2019 Fight in Leveraged Loans Is Lost |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cov-lite-fight-leveraged-loans-110012689.html |website=Bloomberg News |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Chinese debt ==\nThe [[China|Chinese]] government's reaction to the 2009 financial crisis was to direct [[List of banks in China|banks]] to loan to [[State-owned enterprises of China|Chinese state-owned enterprises]] (SOEs), which then built factories and equipment to stimulate the economy despite the lack of demand for the products created. The economic activity of SOEs in 2017 was 22% of China's total GDP, though SOEs accounted for over half of China's corporate debt. It is often not clear the degree to which Chinese SOEs are owned by the state, making it difficult to differentiate corporate and [[sovereign debt]]. Government-directed lending gradually shifted from large banks offering loans to smaller local and provincial banks offering lightly regulated [[wealth management product]]s. This \"shadow banking\" sector grew from $80 billion in 2006 to almost $9 trillion in 2018.<ref name=\"CSIS_070917\">{{cite web |title=Does China face a looming debt crisis? |url=https://chinapower.csis.org/china-face-looming-debt-crisis/ |website=Center for Strategic & International Studies |publisher=China Power |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=7 September 2017}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Liu He, May 16, 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice-Premier]] [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]] is the chair of the [[Government of China|Chinese government]] committee coordinating among financial regulators]]\nIn 2017, the [[International Monetary Fund]] estimated that 15.5% of all commercial bank loans in China were made to firms that did not have an operational cash flow sufficient to cover the interest on the loans. A 60% default rate of these loans could result in losses equal to 7% of Chinese GDP. In 2017, both Moody's and Standard & Poor\u2019s Financial Services LLC downgraded China's sovereign debt rating because of concerns about the health of the financial system.<ref name=\"CSIS_070917\"/>\n\nThe Chinese government recognized the risk posed by corporate debt. The [[Five-year plans of China|13th Five-Year Plan]], unveiled in 2015, included financial reforms to reduce capacity in highly leveraged sectors. There were a wide variety of other policies and restrictions implemented to reduce debt burdens and manage the failure of zombie firms. In 2017, the government established the [[Financial Stability and Development Committee]], chaired by Vice-Premier [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]], to coordinate financial regulation, with the full impact of new regulations expected in 2021.<ref name=\"CSIS_070917\"/>\n\nThe [[China\u2013United States trade war]] that began in 2018 forced the government to pause debt reduction efforts in order to emphasize stimulus as both domestic and global demand for Chinese products fell.<ref name=CNBC_171219/> Government attempts to crackdown on risky debt combined with the economic slowdown to quadruple the size of defaults on yuan-denominated bonds from 2017 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Weizhen |title=Chinese companies are defaulting on their debts at an 'unprecedented' level |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/20/chinese-companies-had-record-amount-of-corporate-bond-defaults-in-2018.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=20 March 2019}}</ref> The government subsequently encouraged banks to increase lending, in particular to small struggling firms. In the first half of 2019, local governments issued $316.5 billion in bonds.<ref>{{cite web |title=China's debt tops 300% of GDP, now 15% of global total: IIF |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-economy-debt-idUSKCN1UD0KD |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=18 July 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, both [[Moody's Analytics]] and Fitch warned that Chinese debt was the biggest threat within the \"fault line in the financial system and the broader economy\" posed by overall corporate debt.<ref name=CNBC_171219/> Fitch noted that 4.9% of Chinese private companies had defaulted on bond payments in first 11 months of 2019, compared to 0.6% in all of 2014.<ref name=Reuters_101219/>\n\n== Potential role of corporate debt in a future recession ==\nThe [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] noted in February 2020 that \"today\u2019s stock of outstanding corporate bonds has lower overall credit quality, higher payback requirements, longer maturities and inferior covenant protection\" that \"may amplify the negative effects that an economic downturn would have on the non-financial corporate sector and the overall economy.\"<ref name=\"OECD_Feb2020\">{{cite web |last1=\u00c7elik |first1=Serdar |last2=Demirta\u015f |first2=G\u00fcl |last3=Isaksson |first3=Mats |title=Corporate Bond Market Trends, Emerging Risks and Monetary Policy |url=https://www.oecd.org/corporate/Corporate-Bond-Market-Trends-Emerging-Risks-and-Monetary-Policy.htm |website=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development |publisher=OECD Capital Market Series |accessdate=12 April 2020 |location=Paris |date=2020}}</ref> If the corporate debt bubble bursts, the bonds would be repriced, resulting in a massive loss by the mutual funds, high-yield funds, pension funds, and endowments with corporate bond assets. As with the 2008 crisis, this may result in increased caution by lenders and the shrinking of the entire [[bond market]], resulting in higher rates for individual consumers for mortgages, car loans, and small-business loans.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/> The International Monetary Fund conducted a stress test for a hypothetical shock half as large as the 2008 crisis and found that $19 trillion of corporate debt from eight countries - China, the United States, Japan, the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Italy, and Germany -, or roughly 40% of all corporate debt, would be at risk of default because it would be difficult for companies to raise cash to repay loans that come due.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horowitz |first1=Julia |title=Here's what could really sink the global economy: $19 trillion in risky corporate debt |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/investing/corporate-debt-coronavirus/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn contrast, other observers believed that a crisis could be averted, noting that banks are better capitalized and central banks more responsive than in the 2007-08 financial crisis. In 2019, the McKinsey Global Institute expressed doubt that defaults in the corporate debt market would result in systemic collapses like that caused by the [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> On 12 March 2020, [[Kenneth Rogoff]] of [[Harvard University]] stated, \"I don\u2019t think we have anything shaping up like 2008 or 1929, particularly in the United States.\"<ref name=\"AP_120320\"/> Though he later revised as the situation worsened, stating on 30 March, \"there is a good chance it will look as bad as anything over the last century and half.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kapadia |first1=Reshma |title=The Coronavirus Crisis Could Be as Bad as Anything We\u2019ve Seen in the Last 150 Years: Harvard Economist |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/harvards-rogoff-shares-his-take-on-coronavirus-crisis-51585653300 |website=Barron's |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Concern about COVID-19 related economic turmoil===\n{{further|Coronavirus recession|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nSeveral financial commentators expressed alarm at the [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|economic fallout]] of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and related [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|collapse of the agreement]] between [[OPEC]] and non-OPEC producers, particularly [[Russia]], to prop up [[crude oil]] prices and resulting [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash during the week of 9 March 2020]]. The concern is that this economic instability may initiate the collapse of the corporate debt bubble.<ref name=WaPo100320/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Rich |title=Coronavirus Exposes the Danger of Corporate America's Debt Binge |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-10/coronavirus-exposes-the-danger-of-corporate-america-s-debt-binge |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Oliver |first1=Matt |title=The \u00a315trillion corporate debt time bomb: Global economy at risk from the bond market as virus spreads |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/finance/other/the-c2-a315trillion-corporate-debt-time-bomb-global-economy-at-risk-from-the-bond-market-as-virus-spreads/ar-BB110Qnj |website=MSN |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlson |first1=Ben |title=The bond bubble may be next to burst |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/12/bond-market-bubble-burst-2020/ |website=Fortune |accessdate=12 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The total economic debt owed by non-financial companies in early March was $13 trillion worldwide, of which about $9.6 trillion was in the U.S.<ref name=\"AP_120320\">{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Paul |last2=Condon |first2=Bernard |last3=Bussewitz |first3=Cathy |title=Corporate debt loads a rising risk as virus hits economy |url=https://apnews.com/7cd0108d79c6b4f1ee2e6ec5fc3a2275 |website=AP News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The Chief Investment Officer of [[Guggenheim Partners]] noted on 9 March 2020, \"the overleveraged corporate sector [is] about to face the prospect that new-issue bond markets may seize up, as they did last week, and that even seemingly sound companies will find credit expensive or difficult to obtain ... Our estimate is that there is potentially as much as a trillion dollars of high-grade bonds heading to junk. That supply would swamp the high yield market as it would double the size of the below investment grade bond market. That alone would widen [[yield spread|[yield] spreads]] even without the effect of increasing defaults.\"<ref name=Guggenheim_090320>{{cite web |last1=Minerd |first1=Scott |title=The Butterfly Effect |url=https://www.guggenheiminvestments.com/perspectives/global-cio-outlook/coronavirus-economic-bond-stock-oil-market-effect? |website=Guggenheim Investments |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> At end of the trading day on 9 March the yield spread for junk bonds reached 6.68% from a low of 3.49% on 6 January, as sellers attempted to lure cautious traders with higher yields. The bonds of firms in the energy sector, who make up about 10% of the total junk bond market and were particularly exposed to the Saudi-Russian oil price war, suffered large yield spreads.<ref>{{cite web |title=Market Extra: Oil market crash exposes thin corporate bond-market liquidity |url=https://www.oilandgas360.com/market-extra-oil-market-crash-exposes-thin-corporate-bond-market-liquidity/ |website=Oil & Gas 360 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Doorn |first1=Philip van |title=These energy companies have the highest debt and the most at risk as the oil market collapses |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/these-energy-companies-have-the-highest-debt-and-the-most-at-risk-as-the-oil-market-collapses-2020-03-10 |website=MarketWatch |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pellejero |first1=Sebastian |title=Corporate-Bond Investors Shy Away From Risk |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporate-bond-payouts-grow-in-uncertain-market-11583871508 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> A debt default by energy companies would harm the regional banks of Texas and Oklahoma, potentially causing a chain reaction through the corporate bond market.<ref name=\"WaPo_140320\">{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |last2=Long |first2=Heather |title=With unprecedented force and speed, a global recession is likely taking hold |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/14/recession-economy-coronavirus-jobs/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the spread on junk bonds over U.S. Treasuries increased to 7.42% in U.S. markets, the highest level since December 2015, indicating less willingness to buy corporate debt. As the [[airline industry|airline]] and [[oil industry|oil industries]] faced dire consequences from the economic slowdown and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]], investors became increasingly concerned that corporate bond fund managers dealing with redemption requests from clients would be forced to engage in [[forced liquidation]], potentially prompting other investors to try to sell first, driving down the value of the bonds, and increasing the cash crunch on investors.<ref name=MarketWatch_130320>{{cite web |last1=Oh |first1=Sunny |title=Wall Street fears \u2018flashbacks to 2008\u2019 with forced selling in $9 trillion U.S. corporate bond market |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/wall-street-fear-flashbacks-to-2008-of-forced-selling-in-9-trillion-us-corporate-bond-market-2020-03-14 |website=MarketWatch |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> A concern is that companies, unable to cover their debt, will draw down their credit lines to banks, thereby reducing bank liquidity.<ref name=Barrons_130320>{{cite web |last1=Scaggs |first1=Alexandra |title=Corporate Bond Rout Spares No Corner of the Market as Investors Start Pricing In Recession |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/corporate-bond-rout-spares-no-corner-of-the-market-as-investors-start-pricing-in-recession-51584123309 |website=www.barrons.com |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> An example is [[Boeing]], which declared on 11 March that it would draw down the entirety of a $13.825 billion [[line of credit]] meant to cover costs related to the [[Boeing 737 MAX groundings]] to \"preserve cash,\" resulting in an 18% drop in its stock.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregg |first1=Aaron |last2=MacMillan |first2=Douglas |title=Boeing will cash out $13.8 billion loan and freeze hiring amid coronavirus market turmoil |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/11/boeing-will-cash-out-138-billion-loan-amid-market-turmoil/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Matsepudra |first1=Victoria |title=Something Broke in the Bond Market on Thursday |url=https://www.fool.ca/2020/03/15/something-broke-in-the-bond-market-on-thursday/ |website=The Motley Fool Canada |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en-CA |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> While U.S. banks should have capacity to supply liquidity to companies due to post-2008 crisis regulations, analysts are concerned about funds holding bonds, which were also seeking to build cash reserves in anticipation of imminent client withdrawals during the economic turmoil.<ref name=Barrons_130320/> In the week of 9 March, investors pulled a record $15.9 billion from investment-grade bond funds and $11.2 billion from high-yield bond funds, the second-highest on record.<ref name=MarketWatch_130320/> As of 13 March, the market was pricing in about a 50% chance of recession, indicating future strain if a recession actually came to pass.<ref name=Barrons_130320/>\n\n[[File:Informal Meeting of EU Finance Ministers (26574742095).jpg|thumb|[[European Central Bank]] [[President of the European Central Bank|President]] [[Christine Lagarde]] oversaw the creation of a Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme on 19 March.]]\nFrom 20 February to 16 March 2020, the yield of the [[iBoxx]] euro liquid high-yield index doubled. The market for new European junk-rated corporate debt, including leveraged debt, had effectively disappeared. Around 38 billion euros of debt is due by junk-rated corporate and financial issuers in European currencies by the end of 2021. Analysts were concerned that Eurozone companies vulnerable to the COVID-19 economic downturn, and with debt coming due over the next two years, would be unable to refinance their debt and would be forced to [[restructuring|restructure]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bahceli |first1=Yoruk |title=Surging borrowing costs, vanishing buyers: more pain ahead for European junk bonds |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-junk/surging-borrowing-costs-vanishing-buyers-more-pain-ahead-for-european-junk-bonds-idUSL8N2B97OL |website=Reuters |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> One U.S. analyst on 16 March opined, \"The longer the pandemic lasts, the greater the risk that the sharp downturn morphs into a financial crisis with zombie companies starting a chain of defaults just like [[subprime mortgage]]s did in 2008.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharma |first1=Ruchir |title=This Is How the Coronavirus Will Destroy the Economy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/opinion/coronavirus-economy-debt.html?algo=top_conversion&fellback=false&imp_id=252017655&imp_id=289517520&action=click&module=trending&pgtype=Article&region=Footer |website=The New York Times |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[European Central Bank]] announced a 750 billion euro ($820 billion) bond-buying program, called the Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme, to calm European debt markets.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amaro |first1=Silvia |title=Italian borrowing costs fall sharply as ECB launches $820 billion coronavirus package |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/ecb-launches-new-820-billion-coronavirus-package.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084734/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/ecb-launches-new-820-billion-coronavirus-package.html |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=ECB announces \u20ac750 billion Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme (PEPP) |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/pr/date/2020/html/ecb.pr200318_1~3949d6f266.en.html |website=European Central Bank |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319074257/https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/pr/date/2020/html/ecb.pr200318_1~3949d6f266.en.html |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The PEPP and corporate sector purchase programme were authorized to buy non-financial commercial paper<ref>{{cite web |title=Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/mopo/implement/pepp/html/index.en.html |website=European Central Bank |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Fed action soothe U.S. markets at the end of March====\nIn the week of 23 March, investment-grade firms in the US issued $73 billion in debt, about 21% higher than the previous record set in 2013. These firms were seeking to build cash reserves before the full impact of the recession. For example, the retail-focused businesses [[Nike, Inc.]] and [[The Home Depot]] began the week borrowing $6 billion and $5 billion, respectively. Unusually, about 25% of the debt was being bought by investors who typically trade stocks.<ref name=WSJ_200420>{{cite web |last1=Wirz |first1=Matt |title=Stock Investors Buy Into Corporate Bond Surge |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-investors-buy-into-corporate-bond-surge-11585585858 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Investment-grade yields had gone up as mutual fund and money-market funds sold their short-term bonds to meet client redemptions in previous weeks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wirz |first1=Matt |title=Short-Term Bond Market Roiled by Panic Selling |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/short-term-bond-market-roiled-by-panic-selling-11584542633 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref> The high yields and the announcement by the Fed that it would purchase investment-grade bonds to ensure market liquidity attracted [[hedge fund]]s and other non-traditional buyers seeking a refuge from market volatility.<ref name=WSJ_200420/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gurdus |first1=Lizzy |title=Investors searching for yield should opt for this part of the bond market, market analyst says |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/03/coronavirus-stock-market-bond-etfs-for-the-search-for-yield.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en |date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Scaggs |first1=Alexandra |title=Panic in Corporate Debt Markets Seems to Be Over\u2014 For Now |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/big-luckin-coffee-investor-sells-entire-stake-in-chinese-starbucks-rival-51586257245 |website=Barron's |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> The Fed's attempts to maintain corporate liquidity, including with $687 billion in support on 26 March, were primarily focused on companies with higher credit ratings. The [[Council on Foreign Relations]] opined that due to the dependence of riskier companies on [[commercial paper]] to meet short-term liabilities, there would be a large increase in corporate defaults, unless aid was extended to lower-rated borrowers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steil |first1=Benn |last2=Della Rocca |first2=Benjamin |title=Why the Fed\u2019s Bazooka Will Not Stop a Wave of Corporate Defaults |url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/why-feds-bazooka-will-not-stop-wave-corporate-defaults |website=Council on Foreign Relations |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlso on 23 March, the [[People's Bank of China]] (PBOC) began [[open market operation]]s to inject liquidity for the first time since 17 February, and also lowered interest rates. Chinese firms had sold $445 billion in onshore (yuan-denominated) bonds in 2020, a 12% increase from the first quarter of 2019. This followed Chinese government efforts to increase liquidity, which drove interest rates to a 14-year low. Chinese onshore bond defaults in 2020 totaled 26.8 billion yuan, down slightly from 29.8 billion yuan in the first quarter of 2019, while Chinese debt yields remained stable. However, the PBOC had not taken steps like the U.S. Fed to massively cut interest rates or buy financial assets, indicating wariness by Chinese authorities of rapid debt accumulation.<ref>{{cite web |title=China Corporate Deleveraging Push May Be on Hold for Years |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/china-corporate-deleveraging-campaign-may-160001846.html |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:DSC 0526 (40902628842).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Jerome Powell]], [[Chair of the Federal Reserve|Chair]] of the [[Federal Reserve]], oversaw aggressive measures to stabilize turmoil in bond markets.]]\nOn 30 March, Moody's downgraded the outlook on U.S. corporate debt from stable to negative. It mentioned in particular firms in global air travel, lodging and cruise ships, automobiles, oil and gas, and the banking sector. Moody's also noted that $169 billion in corporate debt is due in 2020, and further $300 billion in 2021, which would be difficult to roll over in the strained economic climate. At the end of March, Goldman Sachs estimated that $765 billion in U.S. corporate bonds had already experienced rating downgrades. Slippage of firms from investment-grade to junk status continued to pose a stability risk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeff |title=Moody's cuts outlook on $6.6 trillion US corporate debt pile to 'negative' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/moodys-cuts-outlook-on-6point6-trillion-us-corporate-debt-pile-to-negative.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Fitch forecasted a doubling of defaults on US leveraged loans from 3% in 2019 to 5-6% in 2020, with a default rate for retail and energy companies of up to 20%. Fitch further forecast defaults in these two markets of 8-9% in 2020, totaling $200 billion over two years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=Jefferson |title=Corporate debt is in serious trouble \u2013 here's what it means if the market collapses |url=https://theconversation.com/corporate-debt-is-in-serious-trouble-heres-what-it-means-if-the-market-collapses-135371 |website=The Conversation |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ability of [[NCR Corporation]] and [[Wynn Resorts]] to raise $1 billion in unsecured junk-rated debt on 7 April was seen as a sign of increased investor tolerance of risk. The previous week, [[Yum! Brands]] and [[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival Corporation]] were able to issue debt secured against their assets.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wynn, NCR deals a sign of yet more risk returning to bond market |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/wynn-ncr-deals-a-sign-of-yet-more-risk-returning-to-bond-market.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=8 April 2020 |language=en |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Some investment funds began spending up to $2.5 billion acquiring loans and bonds that they viewed as becoming undervalued in the chaos of March.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doherty |first1=Katherine |title=Prices Gone Haywire Attract Billions to Dislocated-Debt Funds |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/finance/companies/prices-gone-haywire-attract-billions-to-dislocated-debt-funds/ar-BB12ke8i |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=8 April 2020 |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Also on 7 April, the [[Institute of International Finance]] identified five countries with corporate sectors with high levels of debt and limited cash that were at the most risk from COVID-19 disruption: [[Argentina]], [[India]], [[Spain]], [[Thailand]], and [[Turkey]].<ref name=\"IIF_070420\"/>\n\nOn 8 April, [[South Korea]] began [[South Korean won|won]]-denominated debt purchases of up to $16 billion to provide liquidity to investment-grade firms. This enabled [[Lotte Food]] Co to issue the first won-denominated debt in three weeks on 9 April. Nevertheless, yields on won-denominated corporate debt were at the highest since 2012 amid pessimism about the global economic outlook and impacts upon South Korean firms.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cho |first1=Kyungji |title=Korea Inc. Returns to Debt Market as Virus Fears Stay High |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/korea-inc-returns-debt-market-200000054.html |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the Fed announced that it would buy up to $2.3 trillion in debt from the U.S. market. This included purchase of up to $500 billion in municipal bonds to give state and local governments access to cash as tax revenue falls. It also stated that it would buy debt from \"fallen angels,\" firms that were downgraded to junk after 22 March.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crutsinger |first1=Martin |title=Federal Reserve announces $2.3 trillion in additional lending |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/finance/smallbusiness/federal-reserve-announces-2423-trillion-in-additional-lending/ar-BB12nRxp |website=AP |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Federal Reserve takes additional actions to provide up to $2.3 trillion in loans to support the economy |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/monetary20200409a.htm |website=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=en |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Fed's Primary and Secondary Market Corporate Credit Facilities totals $750 billion. They are designed as credit backstops for U.S.-listed firms rated at least BBB-/Baa3; if downgraded to junk after 22 March, the firm must be rated at least BB-/Ba3 (the highest tier of junk) when a Facility buys the debt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Primary Market Corporate Credit Facility |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/monetary20200409a5.pdf |website=U.S. Federal Reserve |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Secondary Market Corporate Credit Facility |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/monetary20200409a2.pdf |website=U.S. Federal Reserve |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Fed's announcement drove a sharp rise in prices on junk bond [[exchange-traded fund]]s and individual junk-rated bonds, such as [[Ford Motor Company]] and [[Macy's]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duguid |first1=Kate |last2=Davies |first2=Megan |title=Junk Bond Prices Rally After Fed Offers Lifeline to Riskier Credits |url=https://money.usnews.com/investing/news/articles/2020-04-09/junk-bond-prices-rally-after-fed-offers-a-lifeline |website=U.S. News and World Report |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nECB President Lagarde dismissed the idea of cancelling Eurozone corporate debt acquired during the COVID-19 crisis on 9 April, calling it, \"totally unthinkable.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=ECB's Lagarde says large-scale debt cancellation 'unthinkable' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-ecb-debt-idUSKCN21R0T1 |website=Reuters |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> This followed an opinion piece by former ECB President [[Mario Draghi]] arguing that national governments absorbing the cost of debt acquired by companies while economic activity was suspended would be ultimately less harmful to national economies than letting the companies default on their debt and go into [[restructuring]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Draghi |first1=Mario |title=Draghi: we face a war against coronavirus and must mobilise accordingly |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c6d2de3a-6ec5-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |website=Financial Times |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, Bloomberg News reported that Chinese interest rates were so low that Chinese firms were being incentivized to sell short-term debt in order to buy high-yield [[wealth management product]]s. This [[arbitrage]] was attractive as the poor economic climate reduced incentives to invest in [[fixed capital]] and labor. However, it relies on Chinese local and provincial banks remaining solvent to be low risk. Financial analysts emphasized the need for a strong Chinese fiscal policy to channel corporate investment to productive ends.<ref>{{cite web |title=China\u2019s Risky Wealth Products Gain New Appeal in Low Rates Era |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/china-risky-wealth-products-gain-085308146.html |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[UBS]] warned on 16 April that the amount of Eurozone BBB-rated debt had risen from $359 billion in 2011 to $1.24 trillion. UBS estimated a high-risk of downgrades to junk status. The average of its models indicated that about $69 billion in Euro non-financial corporate assets may be downgraded to high yield status. There are many uncertainties, but UBS predicts downgrades like that experienced in 2011-12 at the height of the [[European debt crisis]], but not as severe as those experienced by Europe in the 2007-08 financial crisis.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kollmeyer |first1=Barbara |title=Covid-19 Shock Is Shining a Harsh Light on Europe\u2019s \u2018Fallen Angel\u2019 Problem, Warns UBS |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/coronavirus-is-exposing-corporate-bond-trouble-in-europe-warns-ubs-51587044823 |website=Barron's |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, ''The New York Times'' reported that U.S. corporations had drawn more than $200 billion from existing credit lines during the COVID-19 crisis, far more than had been extended in the 2008 crisis. It noted that debt-laden firms \"may be forced to choose between skipping loan payments and laying off workers.\" The [[International Association of Credit Portfolio Managers]] forecast that credit risk would greatly increase over the next three months.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |title=Record government and corporate debt risks \u2018tipping point\u2019 after pandemic passes |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/04/18/record-government-corporate-debt-risk-tipping-point-after-pandemic-passes/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=19 April 2020 |language=en |format=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of countries by corporate debt]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Financial bubbles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corporate debt bubble}}\n[[Category:2000s economic history]]\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial economics]]\n[[Category:Interest rates]]\n[[Category:Economic bubbles]]\n[[Category:Commercial bonds]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mass acquisition of low-quality corporate bonds by investors in the late 2010s and 2020}}\n{{globalize|date=March 2020}}\nThe \"'''corporate debt bubble'''\" refers to the large increase in [[corporate bonds]], excluding that of [[financial institution]]s, following the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]]. Global corporate debt rose from 84% of [[gross world product]] in 2009 to 92% in 2019, or about $72 trillion.<ref name=\"Economist_120420\">{{cite web |title=Corporate bonds and loans are at the centre of a new financial scare |url=https://www.economist.com/finance-and-economics/2020/03/12/corporate-bonds-and-loans-are-at-the-centre-of-a-new-financial-scare |website=The Economist |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"IIF_070420\">{{cite web |title=April 2020 Global Debt Monitor: COVID-19 Lights a Fuse |url=https://www.iif.com/Publications/ID/3839/April-2020-Global-Debt-Monitor-COVID-19-Lights-a-Fuse |website=Institute of International Finance |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref> In the world's eight largest economies - [[China]], the [[United States]], [[Japan]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[France]], [[Spain]], [[Italy]], and [[Germany]] - total corporate debt was about $51 trillion in 2019, compared to $34 trillion in 2009.<ref name=\"IMF_161019\">{{cite web |title=Transcript of October 2019 Global Financial Stability Report Press Briefing |url=https://www.imf.org/en/News/Articles/2019/10/16/tr101619-transcript-of-press-conference-on-release-of-october-2019-global-financial-stability-report |website=International Monetary Fund |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=16 October 2019}}</ref> Excluding debt held by [[financial institution]]s - which trade debt as [[mortgage]]s, [[student loan]]s, etc - the debt owed by non-financial companies in early March 2020 was $13 trillion worldwide, of which about $9.6 trillion was in the U.S.<ref name=\"AP_120320\">{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Paul |last2=Condon |first2=Bernard |last3=Bussewitz |first3=Cathy |title=Corporate debt loads a rising risk as virus hits economy |url=https://apnews.com/7cd0108d79c6b4f1ee2e6ec5fc3a2275 |website=AP News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe corporate bond market historically centered in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\">{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Susan |title=Are we in a corporate debt bubble? |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/overview/in-the-news/are-we-in-a-corporate-debt-bubble |website=McKinsey Global Institute |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> The [[U.S. Federal Reserve]] noted in November 2019 that [[leveraged loan]]s, corporate bonds made to companies with poor credit histories or large amounts of existing debt, were the fastest growing asset class, increasing in size by 14.6% in 2018 alone.<ref name=\"Fed_FSR_1109_1\">{{cite web |title=Financial Stability Report - 1. Asset valuation |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/2019-november-financial-stability-report-asset-valuation.htm |website=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=November 2019}}</ref> Total U.S. corporate debt in November 2019 reached a record 47% of the [[Economy of the United States|entire U.S. economy]].<ref name=WaPo_291119>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |title=Corporate debt nears a record $10 trillion, and borrowing binge poses new risks |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/corporate-debt-nears-a-record-10-trillion-and-borrowing-binge-poses-new-risks/2019/11/29/1f86ba3e-114b-11ea-bf62-eadd5d11f559_story.html |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\">{{cite web |last1=Lund |first1=Susan |title=Are we in a corporate debt bubble? |url=https://www.mckinsey.com/mgi/overview/in-the-news/are-we-in-a-corporate-debt-bubble |website=McKinsey Global Institute |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=21 June 2018}}</ref> However, corporate borrowing expanded worldwide under the low [[interest rate]]s of the [[Great Recession]]. Two-thirds of global growth in corporate debt occurred in [[developing country|developing countries]], in particular [[Economy of China|China]]. The value of outstanding Chinese non-financial corporate bonds increased from $69 billion in 2007 to $2 trillion in 2017.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> In December 2019, [[Moody's Analytics]] described Chinese corporate debt as the \"biggest threat\" to the global economy.<ref name=CNBC_171219>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Weizhen |title=Chinese corporate debt is the 'biggest threat' to the global economy, says Moody's chief economist |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/17/chinas-corporate-debt-is-biggest-threat-to-global-economy-moodys.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nRegulators and investors have raised concern that large amounts of risky corporate debt have created a critical vulnerability for financial markets, in particular [[mutual funds]], during the next [[recession]].<ref name=WaPo_291119/> Former Fed Chair [[Janet Yellen]] has warned that the large amount of corporate debt could \"prolong\" the next recession and cause corporate bankruptcies.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kolakowski |first1=Mark |title=Why The Corporate Debt Bubble May Burst Sooner Than You Think |url=https://www.investopedia.com/why-the-corporate-debt-bubble-may-burst-sooner-than-you-think-4587446 |website=Investopedia |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=20 February 2019}}</ref> The [[Institute of International Finance]] forecast that, in an economic downturn half as severe as the 2008 crisis,  $19 trillion in debt would be owed by non-financial firms without the earnings to cover the interest payments, referred to as [[zombie company|zombie firms]].<ref name=\"IMF_161019\"/> The [[McKinsey Global Institute]] warned in 2018 that the greatest risks would be to [[emerging market]]s such as China, [[India]], and [[Brazil]], where 25-30% of bonds had been issued by high-risk companies.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/>\n\n==Low bond yields led to purchase of riskier bonds==\n[[File:US corporate bonds held by mutual funds 2001-2019.svg|thumb|right|300px|The amount of US corporate bonds held by [[mutual fund]]s tripled in the decade following the financial crisis of 2007\u201308.]]\nFollowing the [[financial crisis of 2007\u201308]], the [[Federal Reserve Board]] lowered short- and long-term interest rates in order to convince investors to move out of interest-bearing assets and match with borrowers seeking capital. The resulting [[market liquidity]] was accomplished through two steps: cutting the [[Fed Funds]] rate, the rate that the Fed charges institutional investors to borrow money; and [[quantitative easing]], whereby the Fed buying trillions of dollars of [[toxic asset]]s, effectively creating functioning markets for these assets and reassuring investors. The success of the U.S. Fed in dropping interest rates to historically low levels and preventing illiquid markets from worsening the financial crisis prompted [[central bank]]s around the world to copy these techniques.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\">{{cite web |last1=Cohan |first1=William D. |title=The Big, Dangerous Bubble in Corporate Debt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/opinion/corporate-debt-bubble-next-recession.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=9 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Alster |first1=Norm |title=Companies With High Debt Are Paying a Price |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/business/high-debt-companies-investing.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nHowever, the effect of quantitative easing was not limited to the toxic [[Mortgage-backed security|mortgage bonds]] targeted by central banks, as it effectively reduced the supply of [[Bond (finance)|bond]]s as a class, causing prices for bonds generally to rise and bond [[Yield (finance)|yields]] to lower. For over a decade, the artificially low interest rates and artificially low bond yields, have caused a \"mispricing of risk\" as investors continually seek out higher yields. As an example, [[high-yield debt]], colloquially known as \"junk bonds,\" has historically yielded 10% or more to compensate investors for the increased risk; in February 2020, the U.S. yield on these bonds dipped to nearly 5%.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=ICE BofA US High Yield Master II Effective Yield |url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/BAMLH0A0HYM2EY |website=Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> This indicates that investors flocking to higher yield have bought so much high-yield debt that it has driven the yield below the level needed to compensate for the risk.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/> U.S. corporate bonds held by mutual funds had tripled over the previous decade.<ref name=\"Fed_FSR_1109_4\">{{cite web |title=Financial Stability Report - 4. Funding risk |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/2019-november-financial-stability-report-funding.htm |website=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System |accessdate=10 March 2020 |language=en |date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, 22% of outstanding U.S. nonfinancial corporate debt was rated \"junk\", and a further 40% was rated one step above junk at \"BBB,\" so that approximately two-thirds of all corporate debt was from companies at the highest risk of default, in particular retailers who were losing business to online services.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> The U.S. Fed noted in November 2019 that mutual funds held about one-sixth of outstanding corporate debt, but were acquiring one-fifth of new leveraged corporate loans. The size of high-yield corporate bond mutual funds, which specialize in riskier bonds, had doubled in the decade prior to 2019.<ref name=\"Fed_FSR_1109_4\"/>\n\nWhile trade in corporate bonds typically centered in the U.S., two-thirds of corporate debt growth since 2007 was in developing countries. China became one of the largest corporate bond markets in the world, with the value of Chinese corporate bonds increasing from $69 billion in 2007 to $2 trillion at the end of 2017.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> By mid-2018, total outstanding U.S. corporate debt reached 45% of GDP, which was larger than that seen during the [[dot-com bubble]] and [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=Forbes_290818>{{cite web |last1=Colombo |first1=Jesse |title=The U.S. Is Experiencing A Dangerous Corporate Debt Bubble |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jessecolombo/2018/08/29/the-u-s-is-experiencing-a-dangerous-corporate-debt-bubble/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=29 August 2018}}</ref> Noting negative bond yields in Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and the US in August 2019,  Bloomberg News stated that effectively paying borrowers to borrow is distorting incentives and misallocating resources, concluding that bonds are on a bubble.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Authers |first1=John |title=Bonds Meet the Four Criteria for Defining a Bubble |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-08-13/the-bond-market-is-in-a-bubble-jz9atl25 |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=10 March 2020 |date=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Low interest rates led to increasingly leveraged companies==\n[[File:Corporate Bond Issuance by credit rating, 1995-2019.png|thumb|400px|While issuance of new high-yield (junk) bonds in the US market has been declining since 2012, the issuance of BAA (the lowest rating of \"investment-grade\", including BBB) matched or exceeded high-yield issuance from 2016 through 2019.]]\nCompanies that do not make enough profit to pay off their debts and are only able to survive by repeatedly [[refinancing]] their loans, known as \"[[Zombie company|zombie firms]],\" have been able to turn over their debt because low interest rates increase the willingness of lenders to buy higher yield corporate debt, while the yield they offer on their bonds remains at near-historical lows. In a 2018 study of 14 rich countries, the [[Bank of International Settlements]] stated that [[Zombie company|zombie firms]] increased from 2% of all firms in the 1980s to 12% in 2016.<ref name=WaPo100320>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |title=Fears of corporate debt bomb grow as coronavirus outbreak worsens |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/10/coronavirus-markets-economy-corporate-debt/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> By March 2020, one-sixth of all publicly-traded companies in the U.S. did not make enough profit to cover the interest on their issued debt.<ref name=\"WaPo100320\"/> In developing countries, high-risk bonds were concentrated in particular industries. In China, one-third of bonds issued by industrial companies and 28% of those issued by real-estate companies are at a higher risk of default, defined as having a [[times interest earned]] of 1.5 or less. In Brazil, one-quarter of all corporate bonds at a higher risk of default are in the industrial sector.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> Fitch stated in December 2019 that the majority of Chinese companies listed on A-share markets, namely the [[Shanghai Stock Exchange]] and [[Shenzhen Stock Exchange]], were unable to repay their debt with their operational cash flow and required refinancing.<ref name=Reuters_101219>{{cite web |last1=Zhou |first1=Winni |last2=Galbraith |first2=Andrew |title=China's private firms face record default risk, to stay high in 2020 - Fitch |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/china-markets-default/chinas-private-firms-face-record-default-risk-to-stay-high-in-2020-fitch-idUKL4N28K1YM |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nBond investing in Europe closely followed the actions of the [[European Central Bank]], in particular the quantitative easing implemented in response to the [[European debt crisis]]. In June 2016, the ECB began using its corporate sector purchase programme (CSPP), acquiring 10.4 billion euro in non-financial corporate bonds in the first month of operation, with the explicit purpose of ensuring liquidity in the corporate bond market.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The corporate bond market and the ECB\u2019s corporate sector purchase programme |journal=Economic Bulletin |date=4 August 2016 |issue=5/2016 |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/pub/economic-bulletin/html/eb201605.en.html#IDofBox2 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |publisher=European Central Bank |language=en}}</ref> News in mid-2019 that the ECB would restart its asset purchase program pushed the [[iBoxx]] euro corporate bond index, valued at $1.92 trillion, to record highs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Europe's corporate bond market soars on ECB re-entry bets |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ecb-markets-corpbonds/europes-corporate-bond-market-soars-on-ecb-re-entry-bets-idUSKCN1TM0S8 |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=21 June 2019}}</ref> The increased purchases resulted in 42% of European investment-grade corporate debt having a negative yield, as investors effectively paid less risky companies to borrow money.<ref>{{cite web |title=European top-rated corporate debt with negative yield swells to 40% of market - Tradeweb |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/eurozone-bonds-tradeweb/european-top-rated-corporate-debt-with-negative-yield-swells-to-40-of-market-tradeweb-idUSL8N24X3YY |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=1 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe [[Federal Reserve Bank of New York]] noted in January 2020 that only two U.S. firms had the highest rating of AAA, [[Johnson & Johnson]] and [[Microsoft]], while there was an increased number of firms at the lowest-end, called BAA (on the Moody's rating scale) or BBB (on the S&P rating scale). Investment-grade firms, those with a rating between AAA and BAA, were more highly leveraged than the high-yield (\"junk\") firms. Observing that investors tend to divest bonds that are downgraded to high-yield, the New York Fed stated, \"In the current corporate debt landscape, with a greater amount outstanding of BAA-rated corporate debt and higher net leverage of investment-grade debt overall, the possibility of a large volume of corporate bond downgrades poses a financial stability concern.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Boyarchenko |first1=Nina |last2=Shachar |first2=Or |title=What\u2019s in A(AA) Credit Rating? |url=https://libertystreeteconomics.newyorkfed.org/2020/01/whats-in-aaa-credit-rating.html |website=Federal Reserve Bank of New York |publisher=Liberty Street Economics blog |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nExamples of leveraged corporate debt transactions include:\n* [[Halliburton]] doubled its corporate debt to $11.5 billion between 2012 and 2020; it sold $1 billion in debt in early March 2020 with the explicit purpose of paying off existing debt and has $3.8 billion in debt payments due through 2026.<ref name=WaPo100320/>\n* [[AT&T]] debt ballooned to $180 billion following its acquisition of [[Time Warner]] in 2016. In 2018, [[Moody's]] declared AT&T to be \"beholden to the health of the capital markets\" because of its reliance on continued credit to service its debt load.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/>\n* [[KKR]] sold about $1.3 billion of cov-lite debt in 2017 to pay for its buyout of [[Unilever]], despite Moody's rating the offer 4.99 on a scale of 1 to 5, with 5 being the riskiest.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/>\n* [[Kraft Heinz]] had its credit rating downgraded to BBB- or \"junk\" in February 2020 due to low earnings expectations and the firm's determination to use available capital to provide [[stock dividend]]s rather than pay down debt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kraft Heinz's credit rating cut to 'junk' by Fitch |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-kraft-heinz-ratings-fitch-idUSKBN20823O |website=Reuters |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 February 2020}}</ref> That month, Kraft Heinz had $22.9 billion in total debt with only $2.3 billion in cash assets.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith |first1=Rich |title=Kraft Heinz Debt Is Now Junk |url=https://www.fool.com/investing/2020/02/14/kraft-heinz-debt-is-now-junk.aspx |website=The Motley Fool |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:S&P 500 cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio (CAPE), 2000-2020.png|thumb|300px|The S&P 500 [[cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio]] (CAPE) suggest that the index reached an overvaluation not seen since the dot-com bubble in the late 2010s.]]\nCorporations in the United States have used the debt to finance [[share buyback]]s, dividends, and [[mergers & acquisitions]] that boost share price to a greater extent than before. This has been done in place of long-term business investments and expansions.<ref name=Forbes_290818/> The U.S. [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017|Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of December 2017]] offered a tax holiday under the logic that firms would use the extra profits to increase investments. Instead, it vastly increased an existing trend towards share buybacks, which increase the value of the remaining publicly traded shares and contributed to the rise of stock market indexes generally.<ref name=\"Forbes_210219\">{{cite web |last1=Knott |first1=Anne Marie |title=Why The Tax Cuts And Jobs Act (TCJA) Led To Buybacks Rather Than Investment |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/annemarieknott/2019/02/21/why-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-tcja-led-to-buybacks-rather-than-investment/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=21 February 2019}}</ref> While the [[S&P 500]] has risen by over 300% from its low in the [[Great Recession]], this rise is driven partly by the selling of corporate debt to purchase stock that becomes more expensive due to the purchases. The [[cyclically adjusted price-to-earnings ratio]] for the S&P 500 indicates it is the most overvalued it has been since the dot-com bubble and is around [[Wall Street Crash of 1929]] valuations.<ref name=Forbes_290818/>\n\nThe McKinsey Global Institute cautioned in 2018 against excessive alarm, noting that if interest rates rose by 2%, less than 10% of bonds issued in all advanced economies would be at higher risk of default, with the percentage falling to less than 5% of European debt, which is largely issued by AAA-rated companies.<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/>\n\n==Search for yield results in growth in covenant light bonds==\n{{main|Cov-lite}}\nMost leveraged corporate bonds are \"[[cov-lite]]\", or covenant light, that do not contain the usual protections for purchasers of the debt. In some cases, cov-lite terms may force the purchaser of the debt to buy more debt.<ref name=MarketWatch_200319>{{cite web |last1=Mauldin |first1=John |title=When the U.S. falls into a recession, a credit bubble will explode |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/when-the-us-falls-into-a-recession-a-credit-bubble-will-explode-2019-03-20 |website=MarketWatch |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=20 March 2019}}</ref> By mid-2018, 77.4% of U.S. leveraged corporate loans were cov-lite.<ref>{{cite web |title=Leveraged Loans: Cov-Lite Volume Reaches Yet Another Record High |url=https://www.spglobal.com/marketintelligence/en/news-insights/latest-news-headlines/leveraged-loan-news/leveraged-loans-cov-lite-volume-reaches-yet-another-record-high |website=S&P Global Market Intelligence |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en-us |date=22 June 2018}}</ref> Investors seeking stronger covenants lost the struggle with companies and [[private equity firm]]s seeking to offload risk to the buyers of their debt. A writer for [[Bloomberg News]] opined in February 2020, \"If and when the credit cycle turns, the aggressive push toward weakening protections virtually ensures that recovery rates will be worse than in 2008. But there's no going back now: The risky debt markets are full of cov-lite deals. Investors either have to acclimate to that reality or get out of high-yield and leveraged loans.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chappatta |first1=Brian |title=The \u2018Cov-Lite\u2019 Fight in Leveraged Loans Is Lost |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/cov-lite-fight-leveraged-loans-110012689.html |website=Bloomberg News |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Chinese debt ==\nThe [[China|Chinese]] government's reaction to the 2009 financial crisis was to direct [[List of banks in China|banks]] to loan to [[State-owned enterprises of China|Chinese state-owned enterprises]] (SOEs), which then built factories and equipment to stimulate the economy despite the lack of demand for the products created. The economic activity of SOEs in 2017 was 22% of China's total GDP, though SOEs accounted for over half of China's corporate debt. It is often not clear the degree to which Chinese SOEs are owned by the state, making it difficult to differentiate corporate and [[sovereign debt]]. Government-directed lending gradually shifted from large banks offering loans to smaller local and provincial banks offering lightly regulated [[wealth management product]]s. This \"shadow banking\" sector grew from $80 billion in 2006 to almost $9 trillion in 2018.<ref name=\"CSIS_070917\">{{cite web |title=Does China face a looming debt crisis? |url=https://chinapower.csis.org/china-face-looming-debt-crisis/ |website=Center for Strategic & International Studies |publisher=China Power |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=7 September 2017}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Liu He, May 16, 2018.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice-Premier]] [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]] is the chair of the [[Government of China|Chinese government]] committee coordinating among financial regulators]]\nIn 2017, the [[International Monetary Fund]] estimated that 15.5% of all commercial bank loans in China were made to firms that did not have an operational cash flow sufficient to cover the interest on the loans. A 60% default rate of these loans could result in losses equal to 7% of Chinese GDP. In 2017, both Moody's and Standard & Poor\u2019s Financial Services LLC downgraded China's sovereign debt rating because of concerns about the health of the financial system.<ref name=\"CSIS_070917\"/>\n\nThe Chinese government recognized the risk posed by corporate debt. The [[Five-year plans of China|13th Five-Year Plan]], unveiled in 2015, included financial reforms to reduce capacity in highly leveraged sectors. There were a wide variety of other policies and restrictions implemented to reduce debt burdens and manage the failure of zombie firms. In 2017, the government established the [[Financial Stability and Development Committee]], chaired by Vice-Premier [[Liu He (politician)|Liu He]], to coordinate financial regulation, with the full impact of new regulations expected in 2021.<ref name=\"CSIS_070917\"/>\n\nThe [[China\u2013United States trade war]] that began in 2018 forced the government to pause debt reduction efforts in order to emphasize stimulus as both domestic and global demand for Chinese products fell.<ref name=CNBC_171219/> Government attempts to crackdown on risky debt combined with the economic slowdown to quadruple the size of defaults on yuan-denominated bonds from 2017 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Weizhen |title=Chinese companies are defaulting on their debts at an 'unprecedented' level |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/20/chinese-companies-had-record-amount-of-corporate-bond-defaults-in-2018.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=20 March 2019}}</ref> The government subsequently encouraged banks to increase lending, in particular to small struggling firms. In the first half of 2019, local governments issued $316.5 billion in bonds.<ref>{{cite web |title=China's debt tops 300% of GDP, now 15% of global total: IIF |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-economy-debt-idUSKCN1UD0KD |website=Reuters |accessdate=12 April 2020 |language=en |date=18 July 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, both [[Moody's Analytics]] and Fitch warned that Chinese debt was the biggest threat within the \"fault line in the financial system and the broader economy\" posed by overall corporate debt.<ref name=CNBC_171219/> Fitch noted that 4.9% of Chinese private companies had defaulted on bond payments in first 11 months of 2019, compared to 0.6% in all of 2014.<ref name=Reuters_101219/>\n\n== Potential role of corporate debt in a future recession ==\nThe [[OECD|Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] noted in February 2020 that \"today\u2019s stock of outstanding corporate bonds has lower overall credit quality, higher payback requirements, longer maturities and inferior covenant protection\" that \"may amplify the negative effects that an economic downturn would have on the non-financial corporate sector and the overall economy.\"<ref name=\"OECD_Feb2020\">{{cite web |last1=\u00c7elik |first1=Serdar |last2=Demirta\u015f |first2=G\u00fcl |last3=Isaksson |first3=Mats |title=Corporate Bond Market Trends, Emerging Risks and Monetary Policy |url=https://www.oecd.org/corporate/Corporate-Bond-Market-Trends-Emerging-Risks-and-Monetary-Policy.htm |website=Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development |publisher=OECD Capital Market Series |accessdate=12 April 2020 |location=Paris |date=2020}}</ref> If the corporate debt bubble bursts, the bonds would be repriced, resulting in a massive loss by the mutual funds, high-yield funds, pension funds, and endowments with corporate bond assets. As with the 2008 crisis, this may result in increased caution by lenders and the shrinking of the entire [[bond market]], resulting in higher rates for individual consumers for mortgages, car loans, and small-business loans.<ref name=\"NYT_090818\"/> The International Monetary Fund conducted a stress test for a hypothetical shock half as large as the 2008 crisis and found that $19 trillion of corporate debt from eight countries - China, the United States, Japan, the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Italy, and Germany -, or roughly 40% of all corporate debt, would be at risk of default because it would be difficult for companies to raise cash to repay loans that come due.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horowitz |first1=Julia |title=Here's what could really sink the global economy: $19 trillion in risky corporate debt |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/14/investing/corporate-debt-coronavirus/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn contrast, other observers believed that a crisis could be averted, noting that banks are better capitalized and central banks more responsive than in the 2007-08 financial crisis. In 2019, the McKinsey Global Institute expressed doubt that defaults in the corporate debt market would result in systemic collapses like that caused by the [[subprime mortgage crisis]].<ref name=\"mckinsey_210618\"/> On 12 March 2020, [[Kenneth Rogoff]] of [[Harvard University]] stated, \"I don\u2019t think we have anything shaping up like 2008 or 1929, particularly in the United States.\"<ref name=\"AP_120320\"/> Though he later revised as the situation worsened, stating on 30 March, \"there is a good chance it will look as bad as anything over the last century and half.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kapadia |first1=Reshma |title=The Coronavirus Crisis Could Be as Bad as Anything We\u2019ve Seen in the Last 150 Years: Harvard Economist |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/harvards-rogoff-shares-his-take-on-coronavirus-crisis-51585653300 |website=Barron's |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Concern about COVID-19 related economic turmoil===\n{{further|Coronavirus recession|Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nSeveral financial commentators expressed alarm at the [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|economic fallout]] of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and related [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|collapse of the agreement]] between [[OPEC]] and non-OPEC producers, particularly [[Russia]], to prop up [[crude oil]] prices and resulting [[2020 stock market crash|stock market crash during the week of 9 March 2020]]. The concern is that this economic instability may initiate the collapse of the corporate debt bubble.<ref name=WaPo100320/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Rich |title=Coronavirus Exposes the Danger of Corporate America's Debt Binge |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-10/coronavirus-exposes-the-danger-of-corporate-america-s-debt-binge |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Oliver |first1=Matt |title=The \u00a315trillion corporate debt time bomb: Global economy at risk from the bond market as virus spreads |url=https://www.msn.com/en-gb/finance/other/the-c2-a315trillion-corporate-debt-time-bomb-global-economy-at-risk-from-the-bond-market-as-virus-spreads/ar-BB110Qnj |website=MSN |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlson |first1=Ben |title=The bond bubble may be next to burst |url=https://fortune.com/2020/03/12/bond-market-bubble-burst-2020/ |website=Fortune |accessdate=12 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> The total economic debt owed by non-financial companies in early March was $13 trillion worldwide, of which about $9.6 trillion was in the U.S.<ref name=\"AP_120320\">{{cite web |last1=Wiseman |first1=Paul |last2=Condon |first2=Bernard |last3=Bussewitz |first3=Cathy |title=Corporate debt loads a rising risk as virus hits economy |url=https://apnews.com/7cd0108d79c6b4f1ee2e6ec5fc3a2275 |website=AP News |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> The Chief Investment Officer of [[Guggenheim Partners]] noted on 9 March 2020, \"the overleveraged corporate sector [is] about to face the prospect that new-issue bond markets may seize up, as they did last week, and that even seemingly sound companies will find credit expensive or difficult to obtain ... Our estimate is that there is potentially as much as a trillion dollars of high-grade bonds heading to junk. That supply would swamp the high yield market as it would double the size of the below investment grade bond market. That alone would widen [[yield spread|[yield] spreads]] even without the effect of increasing defaults.\"<ref name=Guggenheim_090320>{{cite web |last1=Minerd |first1=Scott |title=The Butterfly Effect |url=https://www.guggenheiminvestments.com/perspectives/global-cio-outlook/coronavirus-economic-bond-stock-oil-market-effect? |website=Guggenheim Investments |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> At end of the trading day on 9 March the yield spread for junk bonds reached 6.68% from a low of 3.49% on 6 January, as sellers attempted to lure cautious traders with higher yields. The bonds of firms in the energy sector, who make up about 10% of the total junk bond market and were particularly exposed to the Saudi-Russian oil price war, suffered large yield spreads.<ref>{{cite web |title=Market Extra: Oil market crash exposes thin corporate bond-market liquidity |url=https://www.oilandgas360.com/market-extra-oil-market-crash-exposes-thin-corporate-bond-market-liquidity/ |website=Oil & Gas 360 |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Doorn |first1=Philip van |title=These energy companies have the highest debt and the most at risk as the oil market collapses |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/these-energy-companies-have-the-highest-debt-and-the-most-at-risk-as-the-oil-market-collapses-2020-03-10 |website=MarketWatch |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pellejero |first1=Sebastian |title=Corporate-Bond Investors Shy Away From Risk |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/corporate-bond-payouts-grow-in-uncertain-market-11583871508 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=12 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> A debt default by energy companies would harm the regional banks of Texas and Oklahoma, potentially causing a chain reaction through the corporate bond market.<ref name=\"WaPo_140320\">{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |last2=Long |first2=Heather |title=With unprecedented force and speed, a global recession is likely taking hold |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/14/recession-economy-coronavirus-jobs/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, the spread on junk bonds over U.S. Treasuries increased to 7.42% in U.S. markets, the highest level since December 2015, indicating less willingness to buy corporate debt. As the [[airline industry|airline]] and [[oil industry|oil industries]] faced dire consequences from the economic slowdown and the [[2020 Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war|Russia\u2013Saudi Arabia oil price war]], investors became increasingly concerned that corporate bond fund managers dealing with redemption requests from clients would be forced to engage in [[forced liquidation]], potentially prompting other investors to try to sell first, driving down the value of the bonds, and increasing the cash crunch on investors.<ref name=MarketWatch_130320>{{cite web |last1=Oh |first1=Sunny |title=Wall Street fears \u2018flashbacks to 2008\u2019 with forced selling in $9 trillion U.S. corporate bond market |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/wall-street-fear-flashbacks-to-2008-of-forced-selling-in-9-trillion-us-corporate-bond-market-2020-03-14 |website=MarketWatch |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> A concern is that companies, unable to cover their debt, will draw down their credit lines to banks, thereby reducing bank liquidity.<ref name=Barrons_130320>{{cite web |last1=Scaggs |first1=Alexandra |title=Corporate Bond Rout Spares No Corner of the Market as Investors Start Pricing In Recession |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/corporate-bond-rout-spares-no-corner-of-the-market-as-investors-start-pricing-in-recession-51584123309 |website=www.barrons.com |accessdate=15 March 2020 |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> An example is [[Boeing]], which declared on 11 March that it would draw down the entirety of a $13.825 billion [[line of credit]] meant to cover costs related to the [[Boeing 737 MAX groundings]] to \"preserve cash,\" resulting in an 18% drop in its stock.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregg |first1=Aaron |last2=MacMillan |first2=Douglas |title=Boeing will cash out $13.8 billion loan and freeze hiring amid coronavirus market turmoil |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/11/boeing-will-cash-out-138-billion-loan-amid-market-turmoil/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Matsepudra |first1=Victoria |title=Something Broke in the Bond Market on Thursday |url=https://www.fool.ca/2020/03/15/something-broke-in-the-bond-market-on-thursday/ |website=The Motley Fool Canada |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=en-CA |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> While U.S. banks should have capacity to supply liquidity to companies due to post-2008 crisis regulations, analysts are concerned about funds holding bonds, which were also seeking to build cash reserves in anticipation of imminent client withdrawals during the economic turmoil.<ref name=Barrons_130320/> In the week of 9 March, investors pulled a record $15.9 billion from investment-grade bond funds and $11.2 billion from high-yield bond funds, the second-highest on record.<ref name=MarketWatch_130320/> As of 13 March, the market was pricing in about a 50% chance of recession, indicating future strain if a recession actually came to pass.<ref name=Barrons_130320/>\n\n[[File:Informal Meeting of EU Finance Ministers (26574742095).jpg|thumb|[[European Central Bank]] [[President of the European Central Bank|President]] [[Christine Lagarde]] oversaw the creation of a Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme on 19 March.]]\nFrom 20 February to 16 March 2020, the yield of the [[iBoxx]] euro liquid high-yield index doubled. The market for new European junk-rated corporate debt, including leveraged debt, had effectively disappeared. Around 38 billion euros of debt is due by junk-rated corporate and financial issuers in European currencies by the end of 2021. Analysts were concerned that Eurozone companies vulnerable to the COVID-19 economic downturn, and with debt coming due over the next two years, would be unable to refinance their debt and would be forced to [[restructuring|restructure]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bahceli |first1=Yoruk |title=Surging borrowing costs, vanishing buyers: more pain ahead for European junk bonds |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/health-coronavirus-junk/surging-borrowing-costs-vanishing-buyers-more-pain-ahead-for-european-junk-bonds-idUSL8N2B97OL |website=Reuters |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> One U.S. analyst on 16 March opined, \"The longer the pandemic lasts, the greater the risk that the sharp downturn morphs into a financial crisis with zombie companies starting a chain of defaults just like [[subprime mortgage]]s did in 2008.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharma |first1=Ruchir |title=This Is How the Coronavirus Will Destroy the Economy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/16/opinion/coronavirus-economy-debt.html?algo=top_conversion&fellback=false&imp_id=252017655&imp_id=289517520&action=click&module=trending&pgtype=Article&region=Footer |website=The New York Times |accessdate=17 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 19 March, the [[European Central Bank]] announced a 750 billion euro ($820 billion) bond-buying program, called the Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme, to calm European debt markets.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amaro |first1=Silvia |title=Italian borrowing costs fall sharply as ECB launches $820 billion coronavirus package |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/ecb-launches-new-820-billion-coronavirus-package.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084734/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/ecb-launches-new-820-billion-coronavirus-package.html |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=ECB announces \u20ac750 billion Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme (PEPP) |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/pr/date/2020/html/ecb.pr200318_1~3949d6f266.en.html |website=European Central Bank |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=en |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319074257/https://www.ecb.europa.eu/press/pr/date/2020/html/ecb.pr200318_1~3949d6f266.en.html |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The PEPP and corporate sector purchase programme were authorized to buy non-financial commercial paper<ref>{{cite web |title=Pandemic Emergency Purchase Programme |url=https://www.ecb.europa.eu/mopo/implement/pepp/html/index.en.html |website=European Central Bank |accessdate=13 April 2020 |language=en |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Fed action soothe U.S. markets at the end of March====\nIn the week of 23 March, investment-grade firms in the US issued $73 billion in debt, about 21% higher than the previous record set in 2013. These firms were seeking to build cash reserves before the full impact of the recession. For example, the retail-focused businesses [[Nike, Inc.]] and [[The Home Depot]] began the week borrowing $6 billion and $5 billion, respectively. Unusually, about 25% of the debt was being bought by investors who typically trade stocks.<ref name=WSJ_200420>{{cite web |last1=Wirz |first1=Matt |title=Stock Investors Buy Into Corporate Bond Surge |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/stock-investors-buy-into-corporate-bond-surge-11585585858 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Investment-grade yields had gone up as mutual fund and money-market funds sold their short-term bonds to meet client redemptions in previous weeks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wirz |first1=Matt |title=Short-Term Bond Market Roiled by Panic Selling |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/short-term-bond-market-roiled-by-panic-selling-11584542633 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref> The high yields and the announcement by the Fed that it would purchase investment-grade bonds to ensure market liquidity attracted [[hedge fund]]s and other non-traditional buyers seeking a refuge from market volatility.<ref name=WSJ_200420/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gurdus |first1=Lizzy |title=Investors searching for yield should opt for this part of the bond market, market analyst says |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/03/coronavirus-stock-market-bond-etfs-for-the-search-for-yield.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en |date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Scaggs |first1=Alexandra |title=Panic in Corporate Debt Markets Seems to Be Over\u2014 For Now |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/big-luckin-coffee-investor-sells-entire-stake-in-chinese-starbucks-rival-51586257245 |website=Barron's |accessdate=7 April 2020 |date=3 April 2020}}</ref> The Fed's attempts to maintain corporate liquidity, including with $687 billion in support on 26 March, were primarily focused on companies with higher credit ratings. The [[Council on Foreign Relations]] opined that due to the dependence of riskier companies on [[commercial paper]] to meet short-term liabilities, there would be a large increase in corporate defaults, unless aid was extended to lower-rated borrowers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Steil |first1=Benn |last2=Della Rocca |first2=Benjamin |title=Why the Fed\u2019s Bazooka Will Not Stop a Wave of Corporate Defaults |url=https://www.cfr.org/blog/why-feds-bazooka-will-not-stop-wave-corporate-defaults |website=Council on Foreign Relations |accessdate=27 March 2020 |language=en |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlso on 23 March, the [[People's Bank of China]] (PBOC) began [[open market operation]]s to inject liquidity for the first time since 17 February, and also lowered interest rates. Chinese firms had sold $445 billion in onshore (yuan-denominated) bonds in 2020, a 12% increase from the first quarter of 2019. This followed Chinese government efforts to increase liquidity, which drove interest rates to a 14-year low. Chinese onshore bond defaults in 2020 totaled 26.8 billion yuan, down slightly from 29.8 billion yuan in the first quarter of 2019, while Chinese debt yields remained stable. However, the PBOC had not taken steps like the U.S. Fed to massively cut interest rates or buy financial assets, indicating wariness by Chinese authorities of rapid debt accumulation.<ref>{{cite web |title=China Corporate Deleveraging Push May Be on Hold for Years |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/china-corporate-deleveraging-campaign-may-160001846.html |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[File:DSC 0526 (40902628842).jpg|thumb|upright|[[Jerome Powell]], [[Chair of the Federal Reserve|Chair]] of the [[Federal Reserve]], oversaw aggressive measures to stabilize turmoil in bond markets.]]\nOn 30 March, Moody's downgraded the outlook on U.S. corporate debt from stable to negative. It mentioned in particular firms in global air travel, lodging and cruise ships, automobiles, oil and gas, and the banking sector. Moody's also noted that $169 billion in corporate debt is due in 2020, and further $300 billion in 2021, which would be difficult to roll over in the strained economic climate. At the end of March, Goldman Sachs estimated that $765 billion in U.S. corporate bonds had already experienced rating downgrades. Slippage of firms from investment-grade to junk status continued to pose a stability risk.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Jeff |title=Moody's cuts outlook on $6.6 trillion US corporate debt pile to 'negative' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/moodys-cuts-outlook-on-6point6-trillion-us-corporate-debt-pile-to-negative.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=2 April 2020 |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Fitch forecasted a doubling of defaults on US leveraged loans from 3% in 2019 to 5-6% in 2020, with a default rate for retail and energy companies of up to 20%. Fitch further forecast defaults in these two markets of 8-9% in 2020, totaling $200 billion over two years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Frank |first1=Jefferson |title=Corporate debt is in serious trouble \u2013 here's what it means if the market collapses |url=https://theconversation.com/corporate-debt-is-in-serious-trouble-heres-what-it-means-if-the-market-collapses-135371 |website=The Conversation |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe ability of [[NCR Corporation]] and [[Wynn Resorts]] to raise $1 billion in unsecured junk-rated debt on 7 April was seen as a sign of increased investor tolerance of risk. The previous week, [[Yum! Brands]] and [[Carnival Corporation & plc|Carnival Corporation]] were able to issue debt secured against their assets.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wynn, NCR deals a sign of yet more risk returning to bond market |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/08/wynn-ncr-deals-a-sign-of-yet-more-risk-returning-to-bond-market.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=8 April 2020 |language=en |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Some investment funds began spending up to $2.5 billion acquiring loans and bonds that they viewed as becoming undervalued in the chaos of March.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Doherty |first1=Katherine |title=Prices Gone Haywire Attract Billions to Dislocated-Debt Funds |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/finance/companies/prices-gone-haywire-attract-billions-to-dislocated-debt-funds/ar-BB12ke8i |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=8 April 2020 |date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Also on 7 April, the [[Institute of International Finance]] identified five countries with corporate sectors with high levels of debt and limited cash that were at the most risk from COVID-19 disruption: [[Argentina]], [[India]], [[Spain]], [[Thailand]], and [[Turkey]].<ref name=\"IIF_070420\"/>\n\nOn 8 April, [[South Korea]] began [[South Korean won|won]]-denominated debt purchases of up to $16 billion to provide liquidity to investment-grade firms. This enabled [[Lotte Food]] Co to issue the first won-denominated debt in three weeks on 9 April. Nevertheless, yields on won-denominated corporate debt were at the highest since 2012 amid pessimism about the global economic outlook and impacts upon South Korean firms.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cho |first1=Kyungji |title=Korea Inc. Returns to Debt Market as Virus Fears Stay High |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/korea-inc-returns-debt-market-200000054.html |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April, the Fed announced that it would buy up to $2.3 trillion in debt from the U.S. market. This included purchase of up to $500 billion in municipal bonds to give state and local governments access to cash as tax revenue falls. It also stated that it would buy debt from \"fallen angels,\" firms that were downgraded to junk after 22 March.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crutsinger |first1=Martin |title=Federal Reserve announces $2.3 trillion in additional lending |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/finance/smallbusiness/federal-reserve-announces-2423-trillion-in-additional-lending/ar-BB12nRxp |website=AP |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Federal Reserve takes additional actions to provide up to $2.3 trillion in loans to support the economy |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/monetary20200409a.htm |website=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=en |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Fed's Primary and Secondary Market Corporate Credit Facilities totals $750 billion. They are designed as credit backstops for U.S.-listed firms rated at least BBB-/Baa3; if downgraded to junk after 22 March, the firm must be rated at least BB-/Ba3 (the highest tier of junk) when a Facility buys the debt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Primary Market Corporate Credit Facility |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/monetary20200409a5.pdf |website=U.S. Federal Reserve |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Secondary Market Corporate Credit Facility |url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/pressreleases/files/monetary20200409a2.pdf |website=U.S. Federal Reserve |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> The Fed's announcement drove a sharp rise in prices on junk bond [[exchange-traded fund]]s and individual junk-rated bonds, such as [[Ford Motor Company]] and [[Macy's]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duguid |first1=Kate |last2=Davies |first2=Megan |title=Junk Bond Prices Rally After Fed Offers Lifeline to Riskier Credits |url=https://money.usnews.com/investing/news/articles/2020-04-09/junk-bond-prices-rally-after-fed-offers-a-lifeline |website=U.S. News and World Report |accessdate=10 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nECB President Lagarde dismissed the idea of cancelling Eurozone corporate debt acquired during the COVID-19 crisis on 9 April, calling it, \"totally unthinkable.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=ECB's Lagarde says large-scale debt cancellation 'unthinkable' |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-ecb-debt-idUSKCN21R0T1 |website=Reuters |accessdate=16 April 2020 |language=en |date=9 April 2020}}</ref> This followed an opinion piece by former ECB President [[Mario Draghi]] arguing that national governments absorbing the cost of debt acquired by companies while economic activity was suspended would be ultimately less harmful to national economies than letting the companies default on their debt and go into [[restructuring]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Draghi |first1=Mario |title=Draghi: we face a war against coronavirus and must mobilise accordingly |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c6d2de3a-6ec5-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |website=Financial Times |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 April, Bloomberg News reported that Chinese interest rates were so low that Chinese firms were being incentivized to sell short-term debt in order to buy high-yield [[wealth management product]]s. This [[arbitrage]] was attractive as the poor economic climate reduced incentives to invest in [[fixed capital]] and labor. However, it relies on Chinese local and provincial banks remaining solvent to be low risk. Financial analysts emphasized the need for a strong Chinese fiscal policy to channel corporate investment to productive ends.<ref>{{cite web |title=China\u2019s Risky Wealth Products Gain New Appeal in Low Rates Era |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/china-risky-wealth-products-gain-085308146.html |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[UBS]] warned on 16 April that the amount of Eurozone BBB-rated debt had risen from $359 billion in 2011 to $1.24 trillion. UBS estimated a high-risk of downgrades to junk status. The average of its models indicated that about $69 billion in Euro non-financial corporate assets may be downgraded to high yield status. There are many uncertainties, but UBS predicts downgrades like that experienced in 2011-12 at the height of the [[European debt crisis]], but not as severe as those experienced by Europe in the 2007-08 financial crisis.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kollmeyer |first1=Barbara |title=Covid-19 Shock Is Shining a Harsh Light on Europe\u2019s \u2018Fallen Angel\u2019 Problem, Warns UBS |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/coronavirus-is-exposing-corporate-bond-trouble-in-europe-warns-ubs-51587044823 |website=Barron's |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April, ''The New York Times'' reported that U.S. corporations had drawn more than $200 billion from existing credit lines during the COVID-19 crisis, far more than had been extended in the 2008 crisis. It noted that debt-laden firms \"may be forced to choose between skipping loan payments and laying off workers.\" The [[International Association of Credit Portfolio Managers]] forecast that credit risk would greatly increase over the next three months.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynch |first1=David J. |title=Record government and corporate debt risks \u2018tipping point\u2019 after pandemic passes |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2020/04/18/record-government-corporate-debt-risk-tipping-point-after-pandemic-passes/ |website=Washington Post |accessdate=19 April 2020 |language=en |format=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of countries by corporate debt]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Financial bubbles}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corporate debt bubble}}\n[[Category:2000s economic history]]\n[[Category:2010s economic history]]\n[[Category:Economic history of the United States]]\n[[Category:Financial economics]]\n[[Category:Interest rates]]\n[[Category:Economic bubbles]]\n[[Category:Commercial bonds]]\n", "name_user": "Featous", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLow interest rates led to increasingly leveraged companies:lkfinancial stability", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Corporate_debt_bubble"}
{"title_page": "Maggie Blue O'Hara", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Maggie Blue O'Hara\n| image        =\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      =\n| other_names  = Maggie O'Hara\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1975|3|16}}\n| birth_place  = [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| occupation   = Actress, writer/director, singer/songwriter, dancer/choreographer; Founder and co-artistic director (2005\u20132014) of [http://www.alltheatreco.com/maggie-blue-ohara All Theatre Art Association], Hong Kong \n| years_active = 1980\u20132018\n| \n}}\n\n'''Maggie Blue O'Hara''' (born March 16, 1975), also credited as '''Maggie O'Hara''', is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[actress]] noted for her [[voice acting]] and her recognisable \"young teenage girl\" voice. She voiced Madison Taylor on ''[[Cardcaptor Sakura|Cardcaptors]]'' and [[Kitty Pryde|Shadowcat]] in ''[[X-Men: Evolution]]''.\n\n==Biography==\nO'Hara appeared in many television series and TV movies, including ''[[X-Files]]'', ''[[Da Vinci's Inquest]], [[Hope Island (TV Series)|Hope Island]]'', ''[[Neon Rider]]'' and three years as a regular on the CBC TV series ''[[Northwood (TV series)|Northwood]]'' and appeared in the made-for-TV movies ''[[Resurrection (1999 film)|Resurrection]]''.\n\nIn 2005, Maggie Blue and her then husband, renowned Hong Kong sand-painting artist and animator Hoi Chiu,<ref>[http://www.alltheatreco.com/hoi-chiu Hoi Chiu profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421233014/http://www.alltheatreco.com/hoi-chiu/ |date=2012-04-21 }}, alltheatreco.com; accessed May 15, 2015.</ref> formed the All Theatre Art Association, which created shows and toured them internationally to places such as England, Canada, Taiwan, China, Singapore, Thailand, Australia and New Zealand. While living in Hong Kong, O'Hara provided voices for name-brand electronic toys such as [[VTech]] and cartoon series such as [[Hello Kitty (TV series)#Hello Kitty and Friends (1993)|Hello Kitty and Friends]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn early 2015, after nearly 10 years in Hong Kong, she returned to British Columbia to live and is continuing with her voiceover work as well as performing and teaching acting skills and children's yoga. She is also a workshop facilitator.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Animation roles===\n* ''[[Barbie and the Rockers: Out of this World]]'' \u2013 Additional Voices\n* ''[[Brain Powered]]'' \u2013 Hime Utsumiya\n* ''[[Cardcaptor Sakura|Cardcaptors]]'' \u2013 [[Tomoyo Daidouji|Madison Taylor]]\n* ''[[Dragon Ball: Curse of the Blood Rubies]]'' \u2013 [[Bulma]] ([[Funimation]] & BLT Productions dub)\n* ''[[Dragonball Z]]'' \u2013 Bulma (Ep. 123\u2013260 ([[Ocean Group]] dub))\n* ''[[Dragon Tales]]'' \u2013 Shelley (Zak Takes a Dive) and Windy (Sneezy Does It) (2001)\n* ''[[Earth Girl Arjuna]]'' \u2013 Juna Ariyoshi\n* ''[[Finley the Fire Engine]]'' \u2013 D.J.\n* ''[[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (film)|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]'' \u2013 Daphne Spankenheimer\n* ''[[Gundam Wing: Endless Waltz]]'' \u2013 Mariemaia Khushrenada\n* ''[[Infinite Ryvius]]'' \u2013 Cullen Lucciora\n* ''[[InuYasha]]'' \u2013 Karan\n* ''[[Jin-Roh: The Wolf Brigade]]'' (movie) \u2013 Nanami Agawa\n* ''[[Mary-Kate and Ashley in Action!]]'' \u2013 Romy Bates\n* ''[[MegaMan NT Warrior]]'' \u2013 Mika\n* ''[[Monster Rancher (anime)|Monster Rancher]]'' \u2013 Holly\n* ''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]'' \u2013 Strawberry Sunrise\n* ''[[My Little Pony Tales]]'' \u2013 Sweetheart, Moki, Halfnot \n* ''[[LEGO Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu]]'' \u2013 Ultra Violet (Seasons 8-9), Harumi\u2019s Mother, Tox (Season 9)\n* ''[[Ranma \u00bd]]'' \u2013 Anna (Ep. 108)\n* ''[[Ronin Warriors]]'' \u2013 Mia Koji ([[Nasuti Yagyu]]) OAVs only\n* ''[[Saber Marionette J]]'' and ''[[Saber Marionette R]]'' (OAV) \u2013 Lime\n* ''[[Soul Taker]]'' \u2013 Sayaka Tachibana\n* ''[[The Adventures of Hello Kitty & Friends]]'' \u2013 Dear Daniel\n* ''[[ToddWorld]]'' \u2013 Stella (Season 1)\n* ''[[Video Girl Ai]]'' (OVA) \u2013 Ai Amano\n* ''[[X-Men: Evolution]]'' \u2013 [[Kitty Pryde|Kitty Pryde/Shadowcat]]\n\n===Live-action roles===\n* ''[[Cold Squad]]'' \u2013 Helen Larson\n* ''[[My Son Johnny]]'' \u2013 Wendy\n* ''[[Neon Rider]]'' \u2013 Jill\n* ''[[Northwood (TV series)|Northwood]]'' \u2013 \n* ''Other Women's Children'' \u2013 Wanda\n* ''[[The X-Files]]'' \u2013 Young Woman\n* ''[[Wiseguy (TV series)|Wiseguy]]'' \u2013 Mary Jane\n* ''[[Beyond Belief: Fact or Fiction]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0641298}}\n*{{ann|person|1086}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:OHara, Maggie Blue}}\n[[Category:Canadian child actresses]]\n[[Category:Canadian voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Victoria, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Canadian singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Canadian television actresses]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Victoria, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n\n\n{{Canada-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{BLP sources|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Maggie Blue O'Hara\n| image        =\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      =\n| other_names  = Maggie O'Hara\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1975|3|16}}\n| birth_place  = [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]]\n| occupation   = Actress, writer/director, singer/songwriter, dancer/choreographer; Founder and co-artistic director (2005\u20132014) of [http://www.alltheatreco.com/maggie-blue-ohara All Theatre Art Association], Hong Kong \n| years_active = 1980\u20132018\n| \n}}\n\n'''Maggie Blue O'Hara''', also credited as '''Maggie O'Hara''', is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[actress]] noted for her [[voice acting]] and her recognisable \"young teenage girl\" voice. She voiced Madison Taylor on ''[[Cardcaptor Sakura|Cardcaptors]]'' and [[Kitty Pryde|Shadowcat]] in ''[[X-Men: Evolution]]''.\n\n==Biography==\nO'Hara appeared in many television series and TV movies, including ''[[X-Files]]'', ''[[Da Vinci's Inquest]], [[Hope Island (TV Series)|Hope Island]]'', ''[[Neon Rider]]'' and three years as a regular on the CBC TV series ''[[Northwood (TV series)|Northwood]]'' and appeared in the made-for-TV movies ''[[Resurrection (1999 film)|Resurrection]]''.\n\nIn 2005, Maggie Blue and her then husband, renowned Hong Kong sand-painting artist and animator Hoi Chiu,<ref>[http://www.alltheatreco.com/hoi-chiu Hoi Chiu profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421233014/http://www.alltheatreco.com/hoi-chiu/ |date=2012-04-21 }}, alltheatreco.com; accessed May 15, 2015.</ref> formed the All Theatre Art Association, which created shows and toured them internationally to places such as England, Canada, Taiwan, China, Singapore, Thailand, Australia and New Zealand. While living in Hong Kong, O'Hara provided voices for name-brand electronic toys such as [[VTech]] and cartoon series such as [[Hello Kitty (TV series)#Hello Kitty and Friends (1993)|Hello Kitty and Friends]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nIn early 2015, after nearly 10 years in Hong Kong, she returned to British Columbia to live and is continuing with her voiceover work as well as performing and teaching acting skills and children's yoga. She is also a workshop facilitator.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Animation roles===\n* ''[[Barbie and the Rockers: Out of this World]]'' \u2013 Additional Voices\n* ''[[Brain Powered]]'' \u2013 Hime Utsumiya\n* ''[[Cardcaptor Sakura|Cardcaptors]]'' \u2013 [[Tomoyo Daidouji|Madison Taylor]]\n* ''[[Dragon Ball: Curse of the Blood Rubies]]'' \u2013 [[Bulma]] ([[Funimation]] & BLT Productions dub)\n* ''[[Dragonball Z]]'' \u2013 Bulma (Ep. 123\u2013260 ([[Ocean Group]] dub))\n* ''[[Dragon Tales]]'' \u2013 Shelley (Zak Takes a Dive) and Windy (Sneezy Does It) (2001)\n* ''[[Earth Girl Arjuna]]'' \u2013 Juna Ariyoshi\n* ''[[Finley the Fire Engine]]'' \u2013 D.J.\n* ''[[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer (film)|Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]'' \u2013 Daphne Spankenheimer\n* ''[[Gundam Wing: Endless Waltz]]'' \u2013 Mariemaia Khushrenada\n* ''[[Infinite Ryvius]]'' \u2013 Cullen Lucciora\n* ''[[InuYasha]]'' \u2013 Karan\n* ''[[Jin-Roh: The Wolf Brigade]]'' (movie) \u2013 Nanami Agawa\n* ''[[Mary-Kate and Ashley in Action!]]'' \u2013 Romy Bates\n* ''[[MegaMan NT Warrior]]'' \u2013 Mika\n* ''[[Monster Rancher (anime)|Monster Rancher]]'' \u2013 Holly\n* ''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]'' \u2013 Strawberry Sunrise\n* ''[[My Little Pony Tales]]'' \u2013 Sweetheart, Moki, Halfnot \n* ''[[LEGO Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu]]'' \u2013 Ultra Violet (Seasons 8-9), Harumi\u2019s Mother, Tox (Season 9)\n* ''[[Ranma \u00bd]]'' \u2013 Anna (Ep. 108)\n* ''[[Ronin Warriors]]'' \u2013 Mia Koji ([[Nasuti Yagyu]]) OAVs only\n* ''[[Saber Marionette J]]'' and ''[[Saber Marionette R]]'' (OAV) \u2013 Lime\n* ''[[Soul Taker]]'' \u2013 Sayaka Tachibana\n* ''[[The Adventures of Hello Kitty & Friends]]'' \u2013 Dear Daniel\n* ''[[ToddWorld]]'' \u2013 Stella (Season 1)\n* ''[[Video Girl Ai]]'' (OVA) \u2013 Ai Amano\n* ''[[X-Men: Evolution]]'' \u2013 [[Kitty Pryde|Kitty Pryde/Shadowcat]]\n\n===Live-action roles===\n* ''[[Cold Squad]]'' \u2013 Helen Larson\n* ''[[My Son Johnny]]'' \u2013 Wendy\n* ''[[Neon Rider]]'' \u2013 Jill\n* ''[[Northwood (TV series)|Northwood]]'' \u2013 \n* ''Other Women's Children'' \u2013 Wanda\n* ''[[The X-Files]]'' \u2013 Young Woman\n* ''[[Wiseguy (TV series)|Wiseguy]]'' \u2013 Ma